text.text:
The Hen and Chickens is a delightful and welcoming pub in Botley, just outside Chesham, managed by Helen. It fields two teams – ‘A’ and ‘B’. The two teams, by the way, are ranked not by quizzing ability but by charisma. So, if you’re interested in seeing how the quiz works and are thinking about setting up a pub team of your own, you can turn up at the pub on almost any Tuesday evening at 8.30 between November and April and find out.

The ‘A’ team had never suffered relegation in its illustrious twenty or so years of history until 2012-13. Fortunately, we were spared the dreaded drop into the abyss of Division Two by the creation of a single division.

Steve (team captain)

Steve, a retired maths teacher, is a former BBC ‘Film Buff of the Year’ competitor and cinema and television are obviously particular strengths. Other subject areas where he excels include pop and classical music, cricket, English literature and anything related to the United States – especially its geography and its boring sports (baseball and football). Areas for improvement: Fulham FC and the breeding habits of the palmate newt. His captaincy displays a skilful blend of authority when he knows he is right and disassociation when he is not (fortunately rather rare).

Jon

Jon is a former civil servant and an unusually civil one at that. He is also the only clean-shaven member of the team, which he claims makes him the most youthful-looking. Of all the team players, his knowledge of English literature is much the best, though he has been known to huff and puff if the definition of literature is broadened to include the likes of John Grisham. He is also particularly strong on football, cricket, 1960s pop music, cinema and current affairs. Knowledge of the finer aspects of palmate newts, however, continues to elude him – along with practically anything else in the broad field of science.

Neil 

Neil is a retired history teacher. He has good knowledge of several subjects including Fulham FC, 20th century French literature, Latin literature (all of which, of course, appear extremely frequently) and the bits of history he knows something about and Richard doesn’t – sadly there are very few of those. He is good on the state capitals of the US, military history and the regnal dates of the kings and queens of England and Britain. Particular areas for improvement: anything to do with numbers, the geography of the British Isles, any of the sciences, cricket. 

Paul 

Paul is a professional illustrator and spent many years illustrating the restaurant column of ‘The Times’ Saturday magazine. Handily, this means he also knows a lot about food – a topic which appears surprisingly frequently in the quizzes. He also has a phenomenal knowledge of popular culture, encompassing not just pop music, TV (including an otherwise team Achilles’ Heel, Coronation Street) and film but also celebrities. Other areas of knowledge include English literature (especially Dickens) and, inevitably, art and artists from the Renaissance to the contemporary era. Areas for improvement: cricket. 

Richard 

Richard is also a retired teacher – this time of history and politics. The only person who knew more about birds spent most of his life in prison. He is our default go-to guy for current affairs and anything related to the political history of the UK and the US. He has an inexhaustible array of knowledge of just about any sport – even the crappy ones like horse racing. Football, cricket and Rugby Union are particularly strong areas and the latter is especially important to the team as the rest of us are clueless about it. He is also very strong on natural history so knows all there is to know about palmate newts. Areas for improvement: Coronation Street and...that’s about it.

Based in Penn Street, the team has been going in one form or another for about 25 years.  Our strengths are literature, birds and Scottish football: our weaknesses are beyond counting. 

As a team we boast winners of Brain of Britain, Fifteen to One and University Challenge, as well Mastermind and Only Connect contenders.  It doesn't seem to help, though.

On our day we're capable of losing to anyone, or indeed beating anyone (even Farnham Common).

Usual result: narrow win

Usual league position: 3rd

Usual mood: resignation with a hint of hope (dashed)

-------------------------------------------------------------

In a bold break with tradition, we managed to actually win something in the 2015/2016 season.  Here's a picture of the guilty parties with the league trophy, which we're keeping warm for Farnham Common.

The Bell at Chartridge is an ideal pub for use as your 'local' or to visit during or after a walk in the Chilterns countryside. Bar snacks or meals in the restaurant are popular, and The Bell is easily found in the centre of Chartridge village on the road out of Chesham towards Wendover. From Chesham follow signs to Chartridge. Chartridge Park Golf Club or Chartridge Conference Centre. Telephone 01494 782878, postcode HP5 2TF.

There have been one or two quiz teams at The Bell since at least the 1980s. In all that time the team has won the cup just once, the plate just once, the long-gone Sunday evening league just once, and we came second in the league a few times. And that's it. "We may not be very good, but at least we turn up", as the saying goes. We do, however, probably have the best record in the league of anyone when playing the perennial title winners Hen & Chickens B. So on our day, we can beat anyone. Sad thing is, that day doesn't come along too often. Do hit "contact us" if you'd like to join our squads of friendly not-quite-Masterminds for whom Tuesday evening means downing a beer or two while enjoying the quiz.

The Loaf won the toss and elected to go first.  They struck swiftly on the first round on the 'pussy in the well', a question which has been set before and on which authorities differ as to the correct answer.  Round 2 was a full house and the Squirrel struck back in the individuals, picking up two bonuses to get their noses in front 24-23.  Rounds 4 and 5 were tied, round 6 went to the Squirrel and round 7 to the Loaf.  The Loaf also took the second individuals 4-5, so the overall scores were now tied.  Round 9 was also tied, so it was all on the last round.  Alas for the Squirrel, the Loaf took it 6-9 for a final result of 68-71 after a nip and tuck battle.

The Loaf were then inspired to produce a perfect set of answers on the beer leg, so it was definitely the Squirrel buying the round.

Bell B took an early lead and won the first round 7-5 but the Hen edged into the lead in the second and moved steadily ahead thereafter to score 80 for the first time this season.  The Hen also secured a rare Beer round victory.

This did not go quite as we had hoped. We lost the toss, were 3-0 down to start with, and it didn't get any better. We did win round 9,  but by then the game was over bar the shouting. We got nine questions wrong, FCSC picked up bonus points on seven of them. Winning the beer leg counts as No Consolation. But for what it's worth, we had the same answer for 16 of the questions, we both got Fay Wray and Hip wrong, but we knew Stewart Island and Rachman.

The jitters of last week were put firmly behind us as we put in a solid display to see off The Bell in a top of the table clash.
A first question bonus on King Kong set the tone but The Bell should feel hard done by on the Johnny Flynn/Thin/Green question that seems to have three answers.
From memory the club won 4 and drew one of the first half rounds and went into the break 11 points up.
The second half was more of the same until The Bell won round 9 but the final result of 65-83 saw the sports club comfortably home.
Elements, postulants, Quiet Americans and Secret Agents all made a contribution.

We lost the beer leg 18-16ish.

In the clash of the Coleshill teams the Bs got off to a flying start by taking rounds 1 and 2 by 9-6. The As came back in the individual round to reduce the deficit to 4. Rounds 4 and 5 finished all square leaving the Bs leading 38-34 at the halfway point. In round 6 the As took the lead by winning it 8-2. The Bs immediately recovered winning the next round 8-4. The individual round proved problematic for both teams but the As won it 3-0. the As then stretched their lead to 4 in round 9. In the final round the Bs recovered and needed to get the final question to tie the game but failed to do so. The As ran out winners by 62-59.

The Plough won the toss but elected to put the Hen in first, a decision they may have regretted from the outset as the Hen won the first round 9-4. Hen B also won the following two round by smaller margins to extend their lead to 8 points before the Plough fought back in rounds 4 and 5 to reduce the lead to 5 points - 36-31 at half time and all still to play for,

Hen B won round 6 by two points but the real decider came in rounds 7 and 8 which went 7-3 and 10-4 to the Hen. That effectively ended any chance of a Plough comeback but it has to be said that the Plough had the rough end of the questions. The Plough did win round 9 but an 11-2 win for the Hen in the final round gave a rather flattering and deceptive final score.

Hen B  also won the beer leg 18-15.

The Squirrel won the toss and went in second.  The first round was (as ever) 8-8, but the Squirrel took the second 9-6 by knowing who makes Infiniti cars.  The individuals were almost a full house, but the Bell were led astray by the Darwin question and went for the bulldog, not the Rottweiler.  The Bell took the 4th round 6-8 (no-one knew that Tom Courtney has essayed the role of Cpl Jones), and the 5th was another full house - so 41-38 to the Squirrel at half-time.

The next two rounds both went to the Squirrel 9-6, and the individuals also went their way 8-6 (an unlucky choice of Joker by the Bell), so the lead was now 11 points.  The penultimate round was 10-4 to the Squirrel for an unassailable lead.

The beer leg was also the Squirrel's by just a single point (countries invaded by the US).

FCSC won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  After two rounds RLB lead 17-14.  The Red Lion fire alarm again failed to go off at this point!  RLB missed their joker in the first individual round, FCSC took it 4-9. The next two rounds went 6-9 to FCSC, and they lead 33-41 at half-time.

The opening round of the second half also went 6-9 to FCSC, the next was tied 8-8. The second individual round was a low scoring affair all round,  4-6 to FCSC.  With round nine going 4-6 and the last round tied at 8-8, the final score was 63-78 to FCSC.

FCSC also romped the beer leg 13-19 (that WAS a near top of the table clash :/)...

Round 1 - 8 all. 
Then we went three down after failing to grab the car question.
a five point turnaround in R3 saw us take the lead and build on it by virtue of three 9-6's in a row.
full houses in Rs 7 and 10 bookended two 6-4's and a final score of 78-63. 
We thought there were some unbalanced questions but that they evened themselves out.

We won the beer leg too, 19-13 and it was nice to see a question about Versace for a change.

This was another closely fought game between these teams. RLA won the toss and elected to go second first.Both sides scored full houses in the first 2 rounds before RLA took a 3 point lead in the individual round. Full houses all round in round 4 before the Hen pulled back the deficit to tie the scores at 38-38. In the second half the Hen dropped a question in both round 6 and 7 to find themselves 6 points adrift before the second individual round. In this round the Hen won 9-5 and followed by taking round 9 by 6-4 leaving the score at 65-67. In the final round both teams scored 7 to leave RLA winners by 74-72. The beer leg was won 19-16 by the Hen. The teams meet again for the fourth time this season in the plate semi-final in a few weeks time in what should be yet another close.

The Squirrel won the toss and opted (against the evidence of the previous two matches) to go second.    The first two rounds were 8-8, but the Squirrel took the first individuals 2-10 by dint of having the easier questions (no bonuses were picked up).  But the Hen came straight back, taking the next two rounds 8-4 and 9-6 to leave them just one point behind at half-time.

The 6th round also went to the Hen, 9-6 and the 7th was another full house, but the individuals again went the Squirrel's way 5-11 (including two bonuses this time, one on the Joker), giving them a 4 point margin.  The last two rounds were both tied, so that's how it finished, slightly flattering the victors.

The beer leg was an honourable 17-17 tie.

RLB won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  After two rounds, RLB lead 16-13, Plough then edged a poor individual round for both teams 3-5. RLB lead 33-29 at half time.

The next two rounds went 7-7 and 6-9, so RLB took a one point lead into the second set of individuals.  Both jokers were taken, RLB took the round 8-5, so the lead opened to four points in favour of RLB.  Round nine was tied at 6-6, and RLB took the last round 8-4 to make the end score 68-60 to RLB.

Plough took the beer leg 13-15.

Another dismal performance by The Bell A, but one that had started so promisingly. We were 39-37 up at half time (largely thanks to the one person in the pub that knows anything about film couples being on our side). After R7 we were still only a point down, then...calamity. The individuals  were lost 11-2 and that was that. The only one we got - whatever the cookery answer was - being the only one that somebody else on the team didn't know. Oh well. We were hopeless in the beer leg as well. Saving ourselves for the cup.

A game of two halves. A 7-7 draw in round 1 followed by a 7-4 win to the Hen in round 2. The individual subjects were not really to either team's liking with the Red Lion winning a low scoring round 5-4. Red Lion also won the next round bringing the scores back to parity at 24-24. Hen B won round 5 7-3 so only four points in it at half time. 

The second half was completely different. The second individuals were drawn 6-6 but the Hen B won every other round, winning the second half by 20 points to end up 71-47 winners. 

Beer leg was 19-17 to the Hen.

Grateful thanks to Rob Sutherland for reading the sometimes impenetrable questions.

Well that would have been a nice toss to have won but Keith blew it by dropping the coin onto Heather's handbag and losing the second go.
From that point on we were in trouble. 9-4 down after R1, 14-8 after R2, the first individuals and R4 were level pegging before we ended the half 43-30 down.
Time to kick ass. R6 we won 6-8, but the Red Lion kicked harder and won R7 9-6.
It looked like we were down and out but an 11-0 swing in the second individuals brought us back into the game and half way through R9 the scores were briefly level before a bad 50-50 on St Paul's saw the Red Lion go back in front and then extend the lead in the final round for a 73-67 win.
Some excellent knowledge and brave punts from the Lion meant we never really got a hold in the game.

Won the bloody beer leg though, 16-13.

The Squirrel won the toss and elected to go second (which may not have proved a good call).  Round 1 went to the Lion B 8-6, with the Squirrel failing on Disney songs.  Round 2 went to the Squirrel by a single point, which led to the individuals.  Here the Squirrel did better, taking the round 9-4 for a 4 point lead.  But rounds 4 and 5 both went to the Lion, leaving them 2 points up at half-time.

The Squirrel struck back taking the slenderest of leads after round 6.  Round 7 was the only full house of the evening, which meant time for the individuals again.  This proved a bit of a 'mare for the Lion: 2-12 and an 11 point lead to the Squirrel.  The Squirrel stretched their advatage by a point in round 9, but lost the final round 8-5, leaving them victors by 66-75.  Without round 8, the Lion would have won by a point.

Superior knowledge of Top Cat and Brigadier Gerard saw the Squirrel also taking the beer leg.

All seemed lost for the Hen and Chicks A after a thumping defeat (2-14) in the first Individual round saw them trail by eight points.  The Plough snapped up four bonus points here while the home team were all at sea - apart from the shipping forecast..  However, the Hen gradually chipped away at the Plough's lead and won the second Individual round - though by a narrower 3 point margin.  Thus, rounds eight and nine were very tense affairs, ending all-square.  Round 10 saw the home team secure a four point victory.

This is the 4th time these two have faced each other this season with the Red Lion leading  2-1 before this evening.  All the matches have been very close and played in a good spirit and this was the closest of them all.  At the end of the ten rounds the sides were 71 all and the reserve questions were brought into play.  The clincher here proved to be the brass bands in the Hen's favour.  The Red Lion could consider themselves unlucky in that they led for 6 of the 10 rounds and the Hen for only one.  The turning point was the second set of esoteric individuals where the visitors picked up just two points.  Clearly they need to spend more time in Wetherspoon pubs playing 1930s horse racing games.The Hen also won the Beer round.

The final score by no means captures the spirit of an extremely close and hard-fought match, with no side ahead by more than two points until the final round, which proved a bit of a disaster for the Hen.

The round scores were (home side first): 8-8; 6-8; 11-8; 6-8; 7-7; 7-6; 7-6; 7-10; 9-6; 9-2.  The only question that raised a quibble was on the second individuals, where both sides had serious birders on board and naturally chose 'Birds' as the joker.  But on the first question "name the smallest flightless bird" both agreed that "Kiwi" wasn't the correct answer and that some sort of flightless rail (WikiP says the Inaccessible Flightless Rail - no, really, I think it's the island that's inaccessible rather than the bird - which is far smaller than any of the three species of Kiwi) was correct.  Nevertheless we went with the answer on the question sheet.

Biggest and smallest animals (particularly birds) don't make for good questions - how are we defining 'big': weight, length, wingspan are all perfectly reasonable interpretations and may well produce differing answers.

There was no 'beer leg' included in our set of questions, so we improvised by borrowing 20 questions from QLL.  The result was 18-17 to the Squirrel.

The good news. The car passed its MOT with just an advisory about the front brakes, and Brentford's win against Villa.
The bad news. The rise of fascism in America, the gutless appeasement shown by our unelected leader, Spurs, and a batting collapse from FCSC that would make a Mike Gatting side proud.
It all started so well as we got nothing wrong in the first four rounds and were 9 clear before the penultimate question of the first half. An interval score of 35-41 looked promising and the lead was soon back up to 9 by the second individuals where it all unraveled. Yes there were tough questions in the last round ( you're never going to get the  emperor when you haven't heard of the empire) but the decline started with two fairly straightforward misses in the individuals which included the joker. Slightly ahead going into the last round we only got the last question right by which time the game was lost and Hen B secured a 74-69 victory.
the league now looks beyond us but surely we'll be ok in the beer leg, or maybe not.
I've put it down as 1-1 as I have to do something and we'll let Peter sort it out again.

The Bell A won the two individual rounds by 12-6 and 12-4. After the second we were 13 points up. Seven pairs of questions later we were two points down. Mellow Yellow seemed to be the best guess, fortunately with that we salvaged a draw. It follows that if we won the individuals by 14 points, then the Sugar Loaf won the team questions by the same amount.  Beer leg questions were absent, I've put 1-1 in just to make the website work

A crunch match between the two teams currently topping the league - a win by FCSC would require the Squirrel to win their final league match in order to retain the title.  An uncharacteristic slip by FCSC on the very first question (misled by the inclusion of 'Principia' in the wording) gave the Squirrel an early 3 point lead.  The Squirrel also shaded the first individuals, but the FCSC took the next round , leaving the Squirrel just 3 ahead at half time.

The FCSC won round 7, narrowing the Squirrel's lead to a single point, but the Squirrel again shaded the individuals restoring their lead.  Round 9 included a question on the missing Shakespeare sequel to "Love's Labours Lost", the FCSC answered "Love's Labours Found" but the correct answer given by the Squirrel was "Love's Labours Won" - both sides argued that the other team should have the points, but FCSC insisted it must go to the Squirrel in a great display of sporting play.  The Squirrel squeaked the final round, too, for a 5 point victory.

The beer leg was an honourable 16-16 draw, but the FCSC sportingly bought the drinks - cheers!

Probably not our best night of the year and for the first time for a while we talked ourselves out of a couple but not enough to matter and the better side won as they have over the course of the year.
Congratulations to the Squirrel and see you in the cup final.

The Hen were still in this game at half-time at 36-38 down and then proceeded to collapse with alarming alacrity in the second half.  The Sugar Loaf were in coruscating form and that was that.  We shall now be concentrating our resources on the Cup Final - Plate, that is.

Another dismal performance from Bell A for whom the term 'mid-table mediocrity' has become an aspiration. Bell A were ahead for the first four rounds, then the lead changed hands three times before the greater knowledge of the home side proved the difference in the final rounds. The beer leg was shaded by The Plough, in a remarkably low score of 13-12 despite every question bar two being answered by someone. Picasso's birthplace and the tennis player being the ones that got away. But Google "Don Budge". Maybe I heard the question wrong.

The Hen B's lopsided victory was a welcome relief after several losses.  The lopsided score is no disgrace to the Harte and Magpies, whose team consisted mostly of scratch players with no experience of the Chiltern League format.  They deserve thanks for trying their hand at quizzing, at which they did well for a first outing.  It proved to be an enjoyable evening for all.

Thanks to Question Master Sally, who also was a neophyte, but who did a splendid job.

It has to be (I hope, modestly) said that the Squirrel were on excellent form, getting only two questions wrong all evening.  That having been said, the result was distorted by a disastrous first individual round going 14-0 to the Squirrel as questions just fell wrong for the H&M (aren't they a Swedish clothing store?)  The Squirrel maintained their form through the beer leg with their first full house for a long time.

A close game which Bell B deserved to win, on the grounds that they were ahead for most of it. Astonishingly the winners managed only one bonus in the whole quiz - sadly for Bell A, that was the difference between the two sides. Preston North End, as you ask. Of the team questions three were picked up for bonus points, but 13 were unanswered by either side. You know them, or you don't. Bell B pick up a welcome first win, mid-table mediocrity looms again for Bell A.

An interesting evening's quizzing as a combination of ridiculously easy questions gave way to some very challenging buggers in the last two rounds. 
FCSC ended R1 with a 3 point lead thanks to Kappa and finished the night only one further ahead but in between we had built an 11 point lead but R9 and R10 saw it firmly eaten away by the A who very nearly nicked it.
 Overall it felt for the first time that yin didn't equal yang but both sides grabbed some fantastic answers and only 4 questions went unanswered. 
Beer leg was 20-19 with Ben Macdui just giving FCSC the edge.

Hen & Chickens B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  They lead 14-13 after two rounds, and after the first individual round the scores were even at 22 all.  Harte & Magpies B took round four 4-9 and kept the 5-point margin through to half-time (34-39).

H&MB's lead extended to 10 points after round seven (42-52), and with some good fortune in the remaining rounds ran out winners 53-76.

H&MB also took the beer leg 16-19.   (19? 'Tiger' instead of 'Lion' :/ )

A good toss to lose for The Plough who went 2nd.The individual round proved the difference in the 1st half which Plough took 12-6.Four rounds were full houses prior to the 2nd individuals which again went in favour of the home team 11-8.Plough won the last 4 rounds and a final score of 82-65.Sugar Loaf hit back in the Beer Leg with a handsome 20-16 win.

The Hen were always chasing this game with the first individual round proving somewhat challenging with a six point loss.  The second individual round offered a brief prospect of a comeback (plus four) as the deficit was cut to four points. Overall, the questions were mostly balanced and accessible - with the exception of Gandhi's assassin who stumped everyone.

A much closer match than the final score may suggest.  Most of the team rounds were ties or just the odd point either way.  The key round was the first individuals, which fell sweetly for the Squirrel taking the round 12-6 - accounting for most of the eventual margin.

The beer leg was an honourable draw 16-16.

With Jon Jacob back from the dark side and a guest appearance from Sir Malcolm Sargeant this was like the old days as a game of nip and tuck between FCSC and the B went down to virtually the last question.
Hen B took each of the first two rounds 9-6 before the sports club pulled three back thanks to marsupials. 
Rounds 4 and 5 were both draws to bring a half time of 36-33 or something around there. 
FCSC gained one and lost on in 6 & 7, the second individuals were a draw, Greenland came a second too late and we went into the last round three down. Amazingly the B blanked on YouTube and the final score was 77 all.
Question feedback this week is a little more mixed; too many easy questions - particularly on the individuals, some good questions spoiled by an extra clue, overall a swing away from 'pub quiz' to more high brow, and just nowhere near enough questions about Africa.
FCSC won the beer leg 19-16.

Harte & Magpies B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  Plough won the first round and they lead 12-13 after round two.  HMB edged into the lead after the first individual round, and had a big round four (9-4). They also took round five and lead 35-27 at half time.

HMB took round six 9-4, and round seven was tied at 7-7.  Plough missed their joker again on the second set of individuals, HMB took the round 10-4, so the lead opened to 19 points in their favour. With all subsequent questions answered correctly apart from the very last one (Cassiopeia, we had that, but thought it was too complicated!), the result went to HMB 73-56.

Plough took some revenge on the beer round, Miss Sweden won it for them! (14-15).

Yes, you did read that correctly. Bell. A. Eighty. Two. Points. Take that, quiz league. We got every team question correct apart from Cluedo and Disco Island. Pretty much quizzing heaven. 42-27 at half time, 66-44 after winning the second individual, then two rounds of 8-8 to close. Nightmare for The Sugar Loaf, and to be fair it was a good toss for Bell A to win. Sugar Loaf won the beer leg.

HMA got off to the best start scoring maximums in the first two rounds to lead 18-10. Bell B took the individual round 10-6 to reduce the deficit to 4 but then unfortunately dropped the next 2 rounds to leave the HMA leading 38-29. Another maximum for the HMA in round 6 extended their lead further but the Bell took the next round 7-4. The second individual round went 5-4 in favour of the HMA as did round 9 with a score of 7-3. In the final round the Bell came back strongly taking it 10-2 to leave the final score at 65-57 to the HMA.

This one was close all the way through: the biggest gap at any point was 6, and that only lasted for one round.
Round 1 was 8-all, as is more or less compulsory this season, but it fell apart a bit for the Red Lion in Round 2 with the first and last questions slipping away, and the Squirrel slurping the bonuses to go 6 up.  Cue a degree of smug overconfidence at the away end, followed rapidly by a spectacular crash in the individuals which went 4-9 to RLA:  back to 1 point. Rounds 4 & 5 were both flat, to leave the match precariously balanced at the half-time refreshments.
Round 6 went to RLA by 2 points, seeing them take the lead for the first time. Round 7 was flat, but the Squirrel squeaked the individuals to go back into the lead by 2 points, which was still the gap going into Round 10.  
So, nervous excitement all round, particularly when the Squirrel dropped the first question while RLA pocketed the bonus.  Cortisol levels gradually lowered however, as the next 2 questions slid past RLA and into the grateful hands of the Squirrel: the round ending up 8:5 to the visitors.

The beer leg finished 19-19, going to the Red Lion on the tie break.
As a team we were unimpressed by the 4 flat rounds in this week's quiz.  It does no-one any favours to have so many gimme questions.

A bad day at the office for the sports club saw them slip to their first defeat of the season against a solid Hen A performance. 
Nearly all the 50/50's went awry and the jokers could have been better allocated.
Tippex, Pinoccio, Seoul, the Yorkshire Dales, Brandenburg and the Gibson Desert all have a lot to answer for.
19 all in the beer leg and a Tottenham loss meant an early night.

A very close match.

First two rounds were drawn before RLB went two points up in the first individuals through superior knowledge of deserts. Reversal of fortune in the next round which the Hen won 9-4 to go 28-25 up but that lead was immediately lost when RLB won the next round 9-6 so all square at 34-34 at the interval. 

Round six was a full house draw but what made the difference was the next three rounds which the Hen won 9-6,10-6 and 7-6. The eight point gap proved too much for the RLB to overhaul in the final round although they did manage to pull one point back.

Revenge in spades in the beer leg which RLB won 20-15 with a superb full house.

Deja Vu all over again as The Bell Derby went the same way as the game earlier in the season. Bell B were ahead at the break and after the second individual round there was nothing in it at 58-57. OK, there was a point in it. But R9 finished the match. What Bell A (75% middle aged men) needed at that point was a cricket question. Ideally, given that Bell B is a team of 100% younger women, a cricket question from 40 years ago. Thank you Trevor, Kanhai and Marshall put Bell A four points up. Then kings born in Scotland and Wales made that seven points, and obscure passes in National Parks made that round 11-2 and the game safe. Phew. Bell B made a point by winning the last round, 73-64. The beer leg went to Bell A as well.

The visitors to the Plough  were The Sugar Loaf, both teams needing a win. The first two rounds were fairly even but the home team gaining a slight advantage ahead. The Plough won a low scoring individual round by 5 points to 3.  The home team lead at the break with an advantage of 34 to 28. The second half was pretty much a mirror image of the first but with the Plough gradually pulling further ahead. The final score was 71 to 51 to the home side. 

The beer leg was also won by the Plough 19 to 14.

This was a very closely contested match until Round 9.  Indeed, there wasn?t a single wrong answer until the first question of Round 7 when the Farnham Common tripped up over the bridge question and the Hen were able to take a slender lead of three points: 59-56.  The individual round then proved the Hen?s undoing with the loss of the joker points on the US states on which the Farnham Common also picked up a bonus. A humiliating defeat, really. We lost the toss, called the individuals wrong, and didn't konos enough. This was a match in which the Hen never quite managed to threaten the Red Lion A's dominance, trailing in all the rounds apart from the drawn first and when they briefly took the lead by one point in Round 7. The Squirrel were out for revenge for their losing the local Wycombe Lions Quiz to the Plough by a hefty margin (both teams being reinforced by a couple of 'ringers').  The Squirrel lost the toss and the Plough elected to take the first question.

The Plough struck back immediately, taking round 4 9-6, but the Squirrel took the next 8-6, for a 7 point lead at halfway after a (much too) set of questions.

The Red Lion exacted a measure of revenge by winning the Beer Round, ending the Hen's unbeaten run.

Round our way we do the recycling on Friday but this week in the Chiltern Quiz League Tuesday night was recycling night with a lot of the questions having a very familiar ring to them. 18-17 in the beer round. Hoorah!!

Bell A took the two individual rounds by a combined total of 20 to 13. Of the other eight rounds, however, we lost five and drew three. For once the team less than the sum of its parts. We were good on EastEnders and racing drivers, not so good on painters or composers. So much for the classical education. No consolation, but we cruised the beer leg. A fine time had by all.

Red Lion A finally got their first win of the season. Having won the toss they got off to a good start taking the first round by 4 points and gradually increased their lead throughout the quiz. At the half way stage the Red Lion lead by 34-26. In the second half the Hen and Chickens A started badly and found themselves 44-30 down. They were unable to reduce this deficit until it was too late when in the final round they won it 9-4 to leave Red Lion A victors by 72-62.

The Plough welcomed the league's newest team, Bell B. The early rounds were fairly even up to the 5th round when the home team scored 2 points and the Bell B scored 9 points, which meant at the break the Plough were 9 points down. The decisive leg was the second individual round when the home team romped ahead with a score of 11 to 4. Finally winning 65 to 60. But a valiant effort from the newcomers.

It was nip and tuck all the way through the evening between two equally matched teams.  The Squirrel's biggest error was choosing to play their joker on the most difficult of the four questions in the first individual round - the Cities question.  Cities are always a tricky question to set because they aren't well defined - there's usually a historic city, but that's often overtaken by the more modern urban area, but to which one is the question setter referring?

Gothenburg is clearly Sweden's second city, but for New Zealand Wellington and Christchurch are very close and it really depends on which definition you use (we called it wrong, natch).  I imagine a lot of people have moved away from Christchurch following the recent disastrous earthquakes, too.

The beer leg was an honourable draw.

The Bell A has decided to be enigmatic this season. The variation this time being that, having lost to the (then) bottom of the league side last week, this week we beat the reigning champions. The difference being that last week we messed up the individual joker, this week we were lucky (as described in The Squirrel's report). The questions were such that it was difficult for The Squirrel to catch up having gone behind. In the beer leg both sides got one wrong - we didn't know that Audrey Hepburn yet another famous Belgian, but we did guess Muddy Waters' role in the origins of the world's greatest rock'n'roll band. And Bell A has now won at The Squirrel three years in a row - albeit that the first two times were in the semi-finals of the cup. Augurs well for a Squirrel v FCSC cup final.

The Hen were chasing this match from the off and trailed a strong Harte team for the first seven rounds.  However, the second individuals proved decisive in enabling the Hen to level the scores and they finished strongly in the last two rounds.  The questions were perhaps a little too easy in the first half and much better in the second.  Occasionally, decent questions were made too easy with the provision of too many clues - the questions on athletics are a case in point.

A game of two halves really as FCSC won the first half by seven and lost the second by four in a half where H&MB didn't drop a point.
We felt for the second week on the trot the questions were a little lopsided and the individual questions (apart from the cities which was essentially two 50/50's) are insultingly simple.
Having said that, there are some real gems in there like the boat questions - more of them please and less of the extra info that turns a good question into a gimme.
Beer leg was 19 all - Cotopaxi cancelled out by Tristan da Cunha.

This was a repeat of last week's league match, which saw a resounding victory for the Squirrel.  The Squirrel won the toss and went second.  Round 1 (surprisingly, not 8-8) went to the bell, 4-6, but the Squirrel came back in round 2 to narrow the gap to 11-12.  The individuals were almost flat except for the final question on which the Bell took a bonus point for a 19-23 lead.  The Bell also took round 4 and were now 7 points up.  But the Squirrel struck back on round 5, leaving the scores 33-37 at half time.

Round 6 saw only 3 questions answered correctly first time, with the Bell having the better of things 3-7. Round 7 went the way of the Bell, 4-10 and the second individuals saw the Squirrel fall to pieces 2-11 for a 23 point deficit and a virtually lost cause for the Squirrel.  Despite taking the Squirrel taking the penultimate round 7-5, the scores finished 53-76 to the Bell.  It's surprising (or is it?) that two teams can play consecutive weeks and the results differ by almost 50 points!

The Squirrel restored some small semblance of honour by taking the beer leg 19-18.

An astonishing turnaround from last week's drubbing in the league. 49 points better off, in fact, as The Bell recovered from losing by 26 to win by 23. 37-33 up at half time became 76-53 by the end as The Bell won the first three rounds after the break 7-3, 10-4, 11-2. Had the captain not ignored 'Gabon' for the .ga domain and taken a tad longer over the 1990s prime ministers, the margin of victory may have been higher. So The Squirrel can take consolation from a likely podium finish in the league, while The Bell's search for silverware takes us to our third cup final in ten years. We lost the beer leg, annoyingly as Nevada and New Mexico are so easily confused, so bought the beers for the second week in a row. Some things never change.

We got off to a bad start by mistaking Chris Bonnington for Ranulf Fiennes but ended R1 one point up before two quickfire full houses were followed by a 6-9 and a 9-6 and a half time score of 40-39.
In the proverbial game of two halves though the match was very different after the break as we steadily built a lead with rounds of 9-3, 9-6, 9-4, 6-5, and 8-2.
We missed one bonus from West Sussex but bagged the rest for a final score of 81-59.

Beer round was 20-17.

We came crashing down to Earth on the individual qualifiers though - Bloody Hell!!

The Lion won the toss and opted to go second (possibly not a wise decision).  A tough sweetie question saw the Squirrel take an early 8-6 lead, increasing to 17-12 on the second round.  The first individuals went 9-5 to the Squirrel, when a 'pastry' joker turned out to be a 'French language' joker.  The 4th round was tied, but the Lion took the 5th to trail 39-33 at halftime.

The next two rounds went 7-5 to the Squirrel, for a 10 point lead, but the second individuals were a triumph for the Lions at 6-12 (at least we called our joker right).  This left a tight 4 point margin in favour of the Squirrel, but as both the last two rounds were full houses, that;s how it finished (with sighs of relief from the Squirrel).  The identical cup fixture in two weeks should be interesting!

The Squirrel also squeaked the beer leg by the odd point.

Round 1, most surprisingly, was not 8-8 as RLA (going first) missed Round Britain Quiz which FCSC failed to pick up. Round 2 made up for that by being a full house.
The first individual round was a high scoring affair that the sports club nicked 10-8  with only Olivia deHavilland eluding both teams although Keith got bloody close by naming her sister.
R4 went 9-6 to FCSC thanks to RLA eliminating Nobby Stiles to leave an easier bonus and with R5 a full house half time came with the scores 36-43.
R6 was another 9-6 as Keith had played cricket at RAF Valley but the Red Lion reversed that in R7 by dint of a bonus on David Frost. However, the second individuals proved the decisive round with FCSC gaining a 10-2 victory and RLA only getting cava right. Needing the club to trip up a full house in R9 effectively ended the match and Harry Kewell saw the sports club pick up another 9-6 in the final round for a score at the death of 86-67 with only one team and one individual missed by the club all night.
Revenge was had in the beer leg as RLA scored a 19-17 victory.
A pleasant night was had by one and all. It was educational and informative about industrial detergent manufacturing and with only a hint of regret that there weren't more questions about Jasper Carrot.
A closer match than the scores suggest, but most rounds were either halved or won by the Sugar Loaf by a point or two.

You can't hope to beat Farnham unless you're on top form and, (sadly) the Squirrel weren't.  We could make excuses about getting (slightly) the rough end of the questions, going second, and our choice of individuals question (particularly in the first half) didn't go well (I think we can safely say that 11-1 isn't a good result), but the final score (our lowest total that any of us can remember) speaks for itself.  We can only hope for a better attempt in the home leg (or the Cup!)

Once again we embraced the arena, battled hardened and ready, The Morgans swathed in scarves to fight the biting cold, Blood axe battling flu demons and Captain Keith with his usual inane grin and bitter twist. Tonight?s visitors are The Squirrel, glowing with quizzing pride and talking about big national quizzes, a battle is waiting and the abattoir has never looked lovelier. The Sage of One Pin Lane escaped from cash flow figures to adjudicate our vicious little scrap. Captain Keith won the toss and chose to go first.
Round one; usually a gentle opener but the Captain calls wrong and we slump there is no hesitation as The Squirrel smash Jehovah?s Witnesses for a first round bonus. Stupid error by and harsh punishment was delivered. 6-9
Round two; inter round team talk puts us back on the straight and twisted. We are perfect and they drop an Oscar winner, Nicky happily lobs Sean Penn on the table and the gap is closed in time for the individuals 15-15
Round three; what glorious line up of options is set before us? Greek, Dog Breed, Food & Drink and Mathematics.
Alan knew his Greek triangles then grabbed a bonus as their captain went the wrong way.
Captain Keith smashed home his joker and followed up with a juicy Snoopy shaped bonus too. 
Nicky glugged down a Newcastle Brown for two points and chased it with a Plymouth Gin bonus shot.
Eric slipped on Florence Nightingales Pie chart, they grabbed the bonus for their first point of the round and then they were thrown by the roulette wheel. Eric missed the Pascal bonus but no matter. We are leading by ten, the Squirrel evaporated like Andy Murray down under.  Nike and Victoria were sitting sipping Absinthe in the bar. 26-16
Round four; we slipped and they grabbed a perfect round but no bonuses the gap is shaved but we are still rampant although heavy blows were raining down. 32-24
Round five; we smashed another perfect round and snatched a Titanic bonus but dropped an airport we are back on track kicking and screaming a famous victory is in sight. 41-28
The half time drinks slipped down as the questions were swapped over we were ready to batter forward and The Squirrel didn?t flinch they wanted to drag themselves back 
Round six; an even round as we both dropped one but gobbled down the squirming bonus points 48-35
Round seven; the questions were getting tougher, Porridge stuck in all our throats but bonus answers slipped down. Rugby gave another bonus as we ploughed on increasing the gap 56-40
Round eight; more individuals both teams struggled Nicky smashed her bonus and Captain Keith recovered a bonus. Alan slipped the Greek alphabet through for two more points while The Squirrel floundered badly. This was their Waterloo 63 -45
Round nine; would we offer a crumb of hope by dropping questions? The evil ruthless streak came through a perfect round was smashed into place, Giant Evils were the final straw 71-51
Round ten; we swept on dropping Norwich Cathedral but it didn?t matter. We were home hosed with our feet up and a mug of cocoa. The Squirrel battled on with a perfect round but too late, the evil FCSC machine had ground on eyeless, joyless and relentless 77-59
Final Score 77-59 a tougher quiz and we had the easier side of the questions. They soundly thrashed us in the individuals last year so honour has been restored.
We feasted on supper and snuffled through the beer round and emerged victorious 20-19.
So we went home in the glistening moonlight. Our hats tilted at mildly pornographic angle, we whistled the theme from King Kong.

A very close first half. Hen B squeezed two points up in the first round when red Lion missed the moon landing question (although wasn't it Gene Cernan?). Hen B maintained that lead in the individuals despite their classically educated captain not knowing his Greek from his Latin on the joker question. RLA pulled it back to all square in round 4 but the Hen went two points up again in round 5. 38-36 at half time. Rounds 6, 7 and 8 proved to be decisive, the Hen winning those by 9-6, 9-6 and 10-7 to establish and 11 point lead. RLA pulled one point back in round 9 but the Hen ran out 80-70 winners.

Hen B also won the beer leg 20-18, Michael Caine and Wolverine proving the difference.

A game of two halves, Red Lion had a commanding 36-22 lead at half time, but despite a zero round eight for Bell, they finished strongly and 'won' the second half, with the final score being 64-53.

Bell continued their good form into the beer leg, winning it 17-18.

A really good game and really good questions. Questions which made you pleased about getting them right, and then "oh yes I did know that" on other occasions. Florence Nightingale a mathematician? Er, yes, we had heard that. And that rugby player that won the game that Wales stole in the last minute - knew it was a brother, even got as far as Scott, but then got stuck on Hastings. Oh well. First round to The Bell, second to The Plough, appalling individual round for both, Bell pull ahead to be 32-28 up at the break. Plough get back to within a point after Round Six, but losing the second individual round 11-6 doesn't help them and The Bell pulled further away at the finish. They won the Beer Leg, well done to them. We had Dorchester then changed it, and didn't know that Morning Star was also a weapon.

After a severe drubbing in the reverse fixture earlier in the season, the Hen approached the match with a degree of trepidation, especially after a run of defeats.  However, the Hen exacted a measure of revenge on this occasion.  The individuals saw honours fairly evenly shared and while the Bell managed to get ahead in two rounds it was never more than by a point and not enough to turn the match in their favour.

Maybe it just seems that way, but playing Hen B there are always lots of classical music questions, and playing Hen A there are plenty of film questions. Anyway, this was a strange game. Hen A deserved to win having led for all of the match. Both sides won four rounds and drew two, they won theirs by more than we did. Ultimately playing the joker on the "obscure rivers named for colours" and "obscure pop hit from 1953" questions did for us. No, that's not what they were actually called.

The Squirrel against the Hen 'B' is usually a close match, and this one lived up to expectations.  The only difference between the two teams in the first half was a single question in the individuals (the so-called 'chess' round, which turned out not to be about chess at all).  So the Squirrel were 36-33 up at half time.

The Hen struck back, taking round 6 9-6 to level the scores.  But the Squirrel took the next 8-4, so it was on to the second individuals.  This went to the Hen 6-8, only two points between the teams.  The Hen took the penultimate round 6-7, narrowing the Squirrel's lead to a single point - it was all going to be on the last round (again)!

Both teams answered the first pair of questions correctly, but the Squirrel stumbled on the naval rank of Prince Charles.  But The Hen proved no better with his army rank, so the Squirrel kept their noses in front.  Both teams got the last two pairs of questions right, so the Squirrel could breathe again, having taken the match 68-67,.

The Hen strolled the beer leg 19-16, only missing a perfect score by the narrowest of margins.

Questionmaster Richard Cowan stepped in for Eric Bloodaxe but as long as there are no questions on shipping forecast areas, monarchy, horseracing, boxing, US States, US geography, EastEnders or the bible we'll be fine.
D'oh!!!!!
As it was we were still fine in what we all though was a tricky week.
8 all as ever in R1 was followed by a steady build to reach a half time score of 41-26 but the second half was a tougher affair with the Bell struggling on the second individuals which no one loved.
Final score was 75-42 with a 20-10 beer leg giving us our second full house in a row.

 .

RLB won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  First round 8-8!  SL took the second round 9-6, but RLB took the first individual round 4-11 (lucky to have poetry/film buff on chess!).  SL rallied in the next two rounds 8-2 and 8-6 to make the half-time score 37-33 in their favour.

The next two rounds went to RLB 6-9, as did the second individual round (lucky to have an opera buff on er..opera!).  With round nine also going to RLB 4-6, the score was 59-66 going into the last round.  RLB held firm (losing the last round 7-6!), the final score was 66-72.

SL won the beer leg 19-18

The Squirrel lost the toss and the Bell opted to go second, which meant the Squirrel opening for the first time in a couple of seasons.

The Squirrel got off to a flying start with a 10-4 first round.  Round 2 was an 8-8 tie and the Squirrel took the individuals 8-7.  Round 4 was again 10-4 to the Squirrel (despite the incorrect heraldry question (again)).  A single point advantage to the squirrel on the fifth round saw them lead at half time by 43-29.

Round 6 was 10-4 to the Squirrel again, and round 6 was a much tougher one for both teams, but the Squirrel took it 5-3.  The Squirrel  took the individuals 7-2, but the Bell struck back taking the penultimate round 7-5.  The final round went to the Squirrel 7-6 for a convincing 77-51 victory.

Honours were shared on the beer leg 16-16.

The big downside about not writing the report up straight away is that you can never remember anything that happened the night before apart from the obvious - Round One; 8 all.
After that the sports club had the better of most of the rounds but never by much to gradually build a half time lead of 9 points that was cut to seven when we googled the heraldry question that we all thought was wrong.The second half followed the pattern of the first and a strong final round put a very flattering gloss on the score against a team that was shorn of a couple of regulars.
We talked ourselves out of Chad and Golden Delicious amongst others and my friend Paul Angeli prevented me from seeing past him to Michael Angelis who was hiding behind.
Final score 80-57 and a 16-13 win in the beer leg to boot.

RLB won the toss and took the 'B' questions.  Bell took the first two rounds 6-9!  From 12-18 down, RLB went into a 2 point lead (23-21) after taking the first individual round 11-3.  With round five tied at 5-5, Bell struck back ;) to make the score 32-36 at half time.
The next two rounds went 8-4 then 4-8.  With Red Lion edging the second individual round 8-7, the score was 52-55.  Bell edged round nine 5-6, so, still everything to play for?  a tight finish?  No, the last round went 2-11 to Bell, RLB taking the wrong option three times!  Final score 59-72 to Bell A.
A close beer leg, RLB won 17-16 (with apologies again to the very much alive Carla Lane!).

What follows is an attempt to justify how we won this match, as at the time we seemed to have been fluky. OK, here goes. 1 BA answered 42 questions correctly, RLB 30. 2 BA picked up 12 bonuses, RLB five. 3 on the joker questions we lost ten-nil, which doesn't help. 4 Sorry, I feel better now. Fact is that take away the last round BA were matched very closely by RLB that didn't get any luck that was going.  To conclude, score was showing only a four point gap going in to the last round, but Bell A won that 11-2. We didn't lose the beer leg on purpose, but we were happy to buy our hosts a drink. They got Bolivia, we scrubbed it out in favour of Argentina. Bah!

The Squirrel won the toss and opted to go second - not the best decision of the evening.  They were steamrollered by the FCSC, who missed only 4 questions all evening (though the Squirrel did pick up 3 of them as bonuses).

Congratulations to Farnham, honours even for the season.  They also took the beer leg, with three of our 50:50s all going the wrong way.  The story of the evening!

It felt like a nice toss to lose as the Squirrel opted to go second and promptly got on the wrong side of a couple of nasty questions to end the round at 8-4.
Round two was a full house and R3 looked to be going the same way but the Squirrel dropped their Animal Farm joker although they did claw a bonus back via the horned toad. However FCSC's 8 point half time lead was resumed on the last question of R5 where the club grabbed Fast Times at Ridgemont High and the break came with the score at 41-32.
Round 6 was a full house as was the second individuals but the other three were all wins for the sports club who had a good day at the office.
I'm struggling to remember any of the questions but I know we didn't get Melanie nor Bristol which surprised the almost Bristolian in the team. 
Final score was a flattering 82-67 and the beer leg was 20 -16 - 15 with H&M A joining in and nearly nicking second place but staggering everyone with their ability to estimate the height of trees.

The Plough won the toss and elected to go second (the first time the Squirrel have gone first this season).  The first round went to the home side by dint of their knowledge of Morrison's HQ location: 9-6.  The Squirrel's superior knowledge of gay MPs restored the balance in the second round, with both teams going into the individuals on 15 points.  A mixed round saw the Squirrel emerge 6-9 winners, and they went on to take the 4th round 4-10.  The Plough took the 5th round 9-6, leaving them trailing by 6 at the halfway mark.

The Squirrel took each of the next 3 rounds by the odd point or two, giving them a 12 point lead.  Round 9 was the only tie (6-6),  putting the match almost beyond reach. In fact the Squirrel took the last round too, for a 64-77 victory.

The Squirrel also (unusually for this season) took the beer leg 14-18.

Another week without Captain Keith and the same pattern of last week was repeated with lots of bad calls on 50/50's and correct answers written down and rejected but we managed to sneak through against  a side that are always a potential banana skin.
6 points down after R2 we pulled back 5 on the first individuals and went ahead in the next round but were never really clear of danger. 
Leeds/Bradford, King/Knight, Bering Island and Iran/Iraq were all called wrong handing gimme bonuses to the Sugar Loaf and after the second individuals the gap was just 2 points but French middle distance runners and escapee John Leyton saw us home. 

The beer round was a draw at 16 all.

After the customary round 1 full house, the Hen pulled six points ahead in round 2. The Bell pulled four of those back in round 3, including capturing the Hen's joker. Unfortunately for the Bell that was as good as it got as the Hen won  all the remaining rounds of the quiz. It has to be said the the Bell were on the wrong end of just about every unbalanced pair of questions.

Hen B also won the beer leg 16-13

Hen won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  The first round was tied 8-8, then Hen won round two 4-10 and did not lose the lead thereafter.  Hen took the first individual round to lead 18-28.  RLB rallied a little in round four, taking it 8-4, but then Hen responded to take round five 6-9 and they lead by 9 points at the interval (32-41).

Rounds six and seven were tied 8-8 and 6-6, and RLB edged the second individual round 8-6.  With Hen leading by seven points (54-61) at this stage, RLB were hoping that the recent trend would continue....but it did not - Hen nailed the last two rounds 4-5 and 4-10 to win at a canter, final scores being 62-76.

RLB got a free drink anyway! They won the beer leg 15-13.

Another win, another close one for Bell A. Scores in first half were 8-8, 8-8, 8-4, 8-6, 8-8. Not a single bonus and the home team answered every question apart from Tim Lawrence. The second half was not so high-scoring but still close - the gap was never more than six points, and down to three in the last round before we got Hessian and they didn't. Ultimately the win was down to us getting six points from the four joker questions, they got nil. As in the first game between the two sides this season, Red Lion A won the beer leg.

The Plough went in first and the first two rounds passed very quickly with full scores.  The individuals were taken 8-5 by the Squirrel, with both sides missing their Joker questions and in both cases a 2-point bonus being picked up by the opposition.  Round 4 was another full house and Squirrel took the 5th 7-5 to give a half-time score of 39-34.
Round 6 was even at 6-6, and the Squirrel just took round 7 by the odd point.  On the second individual round, there were no mistakes with the Joker questions, but the Squirrel again took it 10-7.  The Plough mounted a late comeback, taking the penultimate round 6-4, but the final round was a tie, giving victory to the Squirrel by 73-66.
The Beer Leg ended 18-15 to the Squirrel.

The Hen and Chickens A were able to secure their customary win - the first of the season - in the absence of the team captain.  (Think Fulham post-Magath).  The Hen led for the first four rounds but a resolute Red Lion came back strongly to pull back a six point deficit to finish the first half level with 36 points.  But Round 7 and  the individual round proved their undoing as the Hen went into an 11 point lead.  The difficult Carry On film questions were snapped up by the Hen's Paul and the Cricket questions were very straightforward for both teams.  The two transport questions were perhaps less balanced.  The Red Lion exacted some revenge with a victory in the Beer round and the Hen remain without a win here.

Once again chucking it down at the Sugar loaves the first two rounds were even stevens until FCSC pulled out a three point lead on the first individuals thanks to Roy Hattersley but only one more bonus chance fell their way before half time bringing an interval score of 34-40.
The second half saw the the better chances favour the sports club and rounds 7, 8 and 9 all saw the gap widen before a full house for both teams in the final round and a final score of 64-84. 
Both sides were quietly proud to be wholly ignorant of the shenanigans of Walford Square and only two other questions went begging all night - New Brunswick and the river that wasn't the Vistula.
The beer round was settled by cockles and racehorses as FCSC snuck home by a short head 20-18.    
And finally Cyril, the Sugar Loaves clearly have a new sandwich mandarin as the food was really good.

red Lion 'A' won the toss and opted to go first  first. Another high scoring game with Bell 'A' managing the perfect first half by answering all their questions correctly to lead 44-36 after round 5.  In the second half the Red Lion improved but failed to pull back the deficit to leave the Bell as eventual winners 78-73.

A game of few missed chances. Bell A managed two bonus points, Roberto Mancini and Archie Mitchell. Red Lion A one, the River Ebro. Otherwise the home side only missed six questions, The Bell A only four. Two of those were the Carry On films and the film directors questions, which drew blanks on both sides. Red Lion A did much better in the bed leg, which may or may not have been a consolation.

A game of two halves. Bell B were on storming form in the first half, hardly dropping anything. In contrast Hen B could only manage 2 points in the first individual round, allowing the Bell B to take a 39-33 half time lead. That six point lead was maintained going into the second individuals, which, in a sudden reversal of fortune, the Hen B took 13-2, thus going into the lead for the first time in the match. They eked out a few more points in rounds 9 and 10, leaving a final score of 75-66 to the Hen B, which was in no way reflective of the match as a whole. Bell B might be new to the league but they are definitely not novices. 

Hen B managed a (for them) rare full house in the beer leg which they won 20-16.

A top of the table clash (not a description frequently applied to meetings of these two teams :)!  The Squirrel won the toss, and opted (as usual) to go second.  Round 1 was (as usual) an easy flat 8-8.  Round 2 went to the Bell 9-6 by dint of knowing how many girls were "sitting on the back seat with Fred" (7?  that must have been a tight squeeze!)  So it was the inevitable individuals, which the Squirrel shaded 4-8 to get their noses in front.  Round 4 was a bit of a disaster for the Bell 1-6, and the Squirrel also took round 5 (6-9) for a 9 point lead at half-time.

Round 6 was taken by the Bell 6-2, could this be the start of a comeback?  The Squirrel took the next 6-9 and it was time for the second individuals.  This was tied at 9-9, leaving the Squirrel with an 8 point margin.  The Squirrel managed to squeeze further ahead in round 9 (6-8) and the final round was an honourable tie (7-7).

The Bell avenged their defeat with a well-deserved victory in the beer leg 18-16.

A top of the table clash indeed, but our place at that top table not so much taken as surrendered. And pretty meekly at that. One of those games when it was one or the other, and we went one and it was the other. But we should have got Chile and Bahamas which would have made it more interesting. Oh well, was fun while it lasted. Scant consolation but in the beer leg years of eating biscuits, watching lower-league football and punk-rocking finally proved to have been worthwhile after all.

A decent if not spectacular performance tonight saw FCSC saw us win the first two rounds by three points and the first individuals by 4 before lack of knowledge on popular names and make up allowed the RLB to catch back up. With R5 an 8 all draw half time came with a score of 39-33.
Darts players eluded both teams as we built another 6 points over R6 and R7 before the second individuals proved a strange affair. For once it was blindingly obvious who was getting what but nearly everyone knew everyone else's questions but not their own. Nevertheless we came out of R8 14 up and stretched that out to 22 by the end.
And a full house on the beer leg, 20-16. Hoorah!!

What a good match.
R1 - 8 all, of course. But in a high scoring first half rounds 2, 4 and 5 were also 8 all. In fact each team only dropped one individual each and the half time score of 40-41 was due to FCSC getting the bonus when the Sugar Loaves didn't.
 In the second half we pulled three points further ahead due to our superior knowledge of slasher movies but lost it all in R7 by missing our literary dog. 
We snuck ahead a touch more on the second individuals which went our way 8-6 but R9 gave us a decent cushion as Inspector George Gently slipped into our hands and each team said the right answer during discussions, and then gave a different one, on the Shakespeare question.
R10 was 8 all for a final score of 79-73.
We lost the beer leg 18-17 when we crossed tiddlewinks out at the last second and replaced it with marbles. We lost our marbles.

The Plough won the toss and chose to go second.  The first two rounds were tied (and would have been 8-8, except that both sides failed to get the correct Christian names for Scots inventors).  The first individuals fell nicely for the Squirrel: 2-11, leaving the Squirrel with an 8 point lead at the halfway mark.

Round 6 went to the Squirrel 5-8, but the Plough took the next 9-6.  The second individuals were a tough set, but the Squirrel took it 0-8.  Honours were shared over the final two rounds.  Without the individual rounds, the Plough would have shaded the match by 1 point.

The beer leg went to the Squirrel 15-18.

Hen won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  After two rounds Hen lead 6-13.  RLB only scored their joker in the first individual round, Hen took it 4-9.  After two more poor rounds for RLB, they trailed 26-40 at half-time. 
RLB took the next two rounds 10-4 and 7-4, and the gap closed a mere 5 points at 43-48.  The comeback did not continue - another poor individual round by RLB followed and with Hen finishing strongly in the last two rounds, the final score was 58-74 to Hen A.

The beer leg was tied at 17-17, but Hen closest to the length of the Trent!
*correction - score 13-16 after two rounds!

A close game up to round 8!  Full houses in the first round, a tied 5-5 second round, narrow wins in the next two rounds to Hen A and more full houses in round five - the half time score was 33-37 to Hen A.

Another perfect round six for both teams, then RLB won round seven 9-6, making the score 50-51 to Hen.  A gripping finish on the cards? Yes, but no - after almost pulling back the deficit, RLB lost the last three rounds 6-11, 6-8 and 4-6, so Hen cantered home 66-76. 

RLB took the beer leg 16-15, all down to Vera!
Ouch! But a good time had by all.
A very comfortable win for the Red Lion A winning the first 9 rounds before drawing the final round.

Always looking likely to be a closely fought match, this did not disappoint (although the questions were a little disappointing).  Round 1 and the Squirrel slipped up on Israeli PMs: 9-6 to the FCSC.  But better snake knowledge allowed the balance to be restored in round 2: 15-15.  The first individuals were agreed to be almost insultingly easy: 25-25.  But round 4 produced the only two questions that neither side answered correctly - unfortunately they both fell to the Squirrel leaving FCSC 33-29 ahead.  Round 5 allowed the Squirrel to demonstrate better knowledge of German surrealists, but they still trailed by 1 point at halftime.

The next 4 rounds were not particularly taxing for either team, so the final round would be the decider.  What was the bloodiest battle of the Napoleonic Wars?  Unluckily the FCSC went the wrong way and the Squirrel snapped it up, finishing victors by 81-79.

The Squirrel (probably overcome by a sense of relief) fell well short of the FCSC's perfect score on the beer leg, providing some small consolation for them.

Nip and tuck all the way and a couple of answers within touching distance that couldn't quite be grasped until in the final round one of those slippery buggers went across to the squirrel for an 81-79 win at the death.
High scores by both teams together with a growing sense that the questions are simply too straightforward, particularly on the individual rounds which are junior school level. 
20 -16 in the beer round.

With FCSC looking to recover from their poor start of the previous week, this had the makings of a very competitive match.  The Squirrel won the toss, and (in the face of all experience) opted to go second.  The first round went 6-9 to FCSC with their superior knowledge of Archers geography.  The second round was a full house, which led on to the first individuals.  A slightly obscure set of choices, but the FCSC absolutely cleaned up, winning the round 2-12 for a 13 point lead - against such a strong team, it looked like a mountain to climb for the Squirrel.  Rounds 4 and 5 both finished 8-8, with FCSC having answered every single question correctly, and only one (panto) question going unanswered.

Round 6 saw the first stumble for FCSC, on UK geography, but they still took the round 6-7.  They also got a Christmas Carol question wrong on round 7, and Squirrel picked up their first bonus point of the evening, but FCSC still took the round 5-8 for a 17 point lead going into the second individuals.  These turned out to be another full house (10-10) as did the final two rounds.  The final score saw a fantastic 86 points to FCSC - will this be the highest score of the season?  The Squirrel had to console themselves with the thought that 69 would have been enough to win on many an occasion.

The vital beer leg was an honourable 18-18 draw, with both sides getting two different questions wrong, so there had been only two questions all evening that had gone unanswered.

With Mrs Morgan's return from North of the Wall we were back to full strength for what is generally a very tricky fixture. Last year we nicked it by a point on the penultimate question but with slightly the easier set this contest was effectively settled in the first half where we didn't get a question wrong and had built a half time lead of 13 points.
A couple of stumbles early in the second half weren't enough for the Squirrel to take advantage and with the last three rounds all high scoring ties we came away with an excellent 86-69 win. We've won matches with less than 69 before so will probably chalk this one off as' one of those nights', but in a good way.
Beer leg was an 18 all draw after talking ourselves out of Switzerland and Billericay.

Last year this fixture produced one victory apiece and a similarly hard-fought match was anticipated.  However, the Sugar Loaf was only able to field three players and suffered accordingly, forfeiting two questions in the individuals .  Even so, the first individual round was particularly poor with both teams managing only five points between them and the Hen, without a female team member, was unable to tackle the Chick Lit question with any conviction.  The Beer Round saw a very narrow victory for the home team.

Bell won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  8-8 after round one!  RLB went into a 6 point lead after round two, but Bell took the first individual convincingly to square the scores at 22-22.  RLB won the next two rounds and the score was 31-39 at half time.

Red Lion edged the next two rounds, but again lost the individual round 6-3, making the score 45-54 after round eight.  RLB took the next round, and Bell took the last.  Final score 56-69 to Red Lion B.

A close beer leg, RLB won 14-15 (all on Dallas v Houston!).

glance at the score would hint that this was a good toss to win. Not necessarily so, the trick being that we knew most of their questions as well. Rah, bully for us! We will revert to modesty when we are not top of the league. Ignoring the individuals, each side gets 32 team questions. We got 29 of ours, The Plough picked up two of the bonuses on offer. They missed 12 of theirs, we also picked up a bonus point on all but one. In the quiz, only three team questions were missed by both sides.
9-4 became 18-10 then The Plough won the first individual round (four subjects that nobody wanted anything to do with!) then the next round as well before an 8-8 took the score at the break to a close 38-35 in favour of The Bell. Bring on Round 6! We have never managed a 12-0 in nearly 30 years of doing this - but we would have done had we guessed Derbyshire for being furthest from the sea. We had Warwickshire, they missed the bonus by opting for Northants. 10-0 to The Bell. Sadly for the home team the next round was 9-3 against them as well, so those two rounds were a large part of the winning margin. 
In the beer leg we got three wrong that they got right, but the reverse was also true and we both got the spaghetti question and the herb wrong. Honours even and a fun time had by all.

A closer match than the final score might suggest.  The Bell (physically 'away', but logically 'home') had the tougher set of questions in the first half (put in first by The Squirrel), and were trailing by 9 points at  half time.  They took two of the next four rounds and narrowed the Squirrel's lead to 7 points going into the last round, but the Squirrel took it 10-4.  Our second consecutive maximum score brought home the beer leg as well.

The scrupulously fair draw for the knockout competitions will see us playing the Bell again (our track record against them in the cup is not encouraging) ...

Our sponsors (sugar Loaf) won the toss and went first. A disastrous  first round for the Hen losing it 4-10 followed by two drawn rounds and two losses for the. Hen meant the Sugars taking the first half 40-27 .The second half was little better with the Sugar Loaf winning the first two rounds 9-6. Time for the come-back! The Hen took the Individual round but promptly lost R9. We needed the Sugar Loaf to lose every question in R10 but it was not to be. The final score was a worthy win by the Sugar Loaf . Our hopes were now pinned on the Beer Leg. Alas the win here did not materialise! 15-18 to the Loaf. Ah well! The food was good. It always is when there's a darts match on in the main bar!

I said to myself before I left 'the last thing you must do is leave the questions and scoresheet behind again', and as that was indeed the last thing I did I can't tell you too much about what happened.
FCSC went first first. R1 - 8 all of course. So was R2. We went one up after the first individuals but that was reversed in R4 until  R5 went heavily our way something like 11-2  for a half time 9 point lead. 
The second half was rather different with each round being a consistent two or three point win for FCSC for a final score of 80-60.  
H&MB took the beer leg 17-16.

The Hen won the toss and chose to go first.  Round 1 was a swiftly concluded 8-8, as is traditional.  Round 2 went 6-9 to the Hen with their superior knowledge of 60s TV theme tunes, but Dr Who and TV cookery contests saw the Squirrel take a one point lead after the individuals.  The Hen struck back, taking round 4 4-6 and a full house on round 5 saw the Hen with a single point advantage at half time.

The Squirrel took both the next two rounds 9-6 to open the first significant lead of the evening - but it all fell apart at the second individuals, which the Hen took 3-11.  The Squirrel took the next round 8-6 to leave them still a point in arrears, but the final round went 9-2 to the Squirrel for a somewhat flattering final score of 74-68.  A great game, in which the lead changed hands 6 times.

The Squirrel squeaked the beer leg 20-19 - the anatomical question being the decider (our first maximum of the season).

Plough won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  8-8 after round one!  RLB lead 14-16 after round two.  The first individual round went convincingly to RLB 4-13.  Plough took round four 8-2 (you say subpoena, I say summons!), with the next round tied at 8-8, the score was 34-39 at half time. 

Round six was tied 7-7, and Plough won round seven to make the scores equal at 50-50.  Red Lion edged the second individual round 6-7, so it looked like a close finish would ensue!  But, RLB took the last two rounds 3-8 and 0-7, so the final score was 59-73 to Red Lion B.

A close beer leg, RLB won 16-18.
Annoying. On another night we could (should?) have got; Atherton, Lolita, puffin, Iron Maiden, whichever Mitchell and Cherie Booth. Missed them all.

Very much a game of 2 halves. Bell B won the toss and opted to go first and both initial 2 rounds finished level. Red Lion gained a point lead after the first individual round and led the match 23-22. The Bell then had 2 bad rounds to be 42-28 at the half way stage mainly due to several sport based questions which were not their strength. In the second half the Bell immediately began their recovery taking the next 3 rounds 6-9, 6-8 and 3-4. Round 9 was all square with both teams scoring a maximum. In the final round Red Lion started badly dropping the first 2 questions with the Bell picking up the bonuses as well as answering their 2 questions correctly reducing the deficit to just 2 points. Red Lion were relieved to answer their final 2 questions correctly to finally run out winners 69-65. The beer leg proved a one sided affair with the Red Lion winning 16-9

Going second proved to be the right choice for the Squirrel.  They only dropped 3 questions (Sinatra tunes, English mountains and race courses on the second individual round) during the evening, out of which the Bell picked up 2 bonuses.  Insult was added to injury by the Squirrel taking the beer leg 17-14.
Veni, vidi, vici

Needing a point to secure the title FCSC came out all guns blazing and put in a solid performance with only a couple of hiccups.
R1 - I don't even need to say it do I? 
R2 - We pull out a slight lead with a 9-6 win.
R3 - We win the individuals 8-4 missing our joker (Boost??) but picking up theirs on the same subject.
R4 - a 7-6 win, we miss Vermont but pick up Valentine
R5 - a full house and a half time score of 40-32

R6- 9-4
R7 - 10-4, appropriately
R8 - 10-8, only missing the bonus on Maureen Lipman whose name escaped me although I knew she had an Ology.
R9 - 6 all, dropping St Albans which The Plough picked up.
R10 - 8-4, annoyingly talking ourselves out of Barbour in favour of Belstaff.
Final score - 83/59.
A good win though played in excellent humour with beautifully read questions.

Beer leg - 17-14.

A very close game for four rounds. After the customary full houses in round 1, the Hen B pulled one point ahead in round 2. Hen A then went one point up after round 3 and then it was back to all square in round 4. The real killer was round 5 which went 11-2 to the B team leaving them 41-32 up at the interval. They pulled another two points ahead in round 6 and a further point in round 7. Hen A pulled back two points in round 8 but that was it and with the final two rounds drawn the B team ran out 79-68 winners.

All square in the beer leg which was drawn 18-18.

The Bell A secured fourth place with a win against Red Lion B. The final score flattered the home side, as RLB won the toss and may have regretted going first. The Bell took eight bonus points of the 13 that were offered, RLB just two from seven. American geography, horse racing venues and literary homes being three of those that The Bell picked up. The beer leg was halved, neither side being ashamed to admit to knowing John Cleland as the author of Fanny Hill.
