Bell A profited from rather more sports questions than usual and despite missing out on the first individual joker had a lead at the break which was never lost despite some spirited resistance from Bell B.

The Squirrel won the toss and opted (as ever) to go second.  The first round finished in the, by now traditional, 8-8 tie (though the questions were a bit more challenging than in recent weeks).  Round 2 was 6-7 to the Lion, while the individuals went to the Squirrel 10-8 (no-one correctly identified the protagonist of The Exorcist).  Round 4 went to the Lion 5-8, but the Squirrel struck back 10-4 for a 39-35 lead at half-time (the lead having changed hands 3 times in the first 5 rounds).

Round 6 was another 8-8 tie, but the Lion took the next 4-9 to regain the lead.  The second set of individuals went to the Squirrel 10-6 giving them a 2 point margin.  Round 9 was also taken by the Squirrel (9-6) and they took the last round as well (8-6) for a rather flattering final score of 78-71 after a very close match in which the lead changed 5 times.

The beer leg was an honourable 16-16 tie.  Both sides felt the questions to have been an improvement over the lacklustre sets of the last few weeks.

This was a closely contested match in all the rounds with the exception of the second individual round.  Up until then the lead had changed several times with the FCSC edging most of them.  After round 7 the Hen ("there's only one Hen in Chesham" rang the chant from the terraces) was behind 49-51 but the Individuals went pear-shaped for the visitors who lost 12-1.  There was no coming back for Farnham with a deficit of nine points and just two rounds to go.  A measure of revenge was exacted for the visitors with  a perfect score of 20 in the beer round.

Round 8 at the Hen & Chickens is a round that will live forever in infamy.
R1 8-8, as ever. then nip and tuck over the next few rounds with the Hen having a one point half time lead and FCSC going two up before the second individuals which was just a complete disaster for us.
Snatched answers, the inability to grasp the very complicated and unusual surname Robinson when it was needed, and just plain old fashioned not knowing conspired for a 12-1 loss and the game gone.
We  clawed a little back for a final score of 69-75.
We won the beer leg 20-17 though for another cheap date.

The Squirrel won the toss and elected to go second (a key decision, as it transpired).  Rounds 1 and 2 were full houses and the individuals went 9-9 (not all of us are old enough to remember the minor characters in 'Dixon of Dock Green').  The Squirrel took a lead in round 4, with better knowledge of teen fiction, and also took round 5 on 'drugs'(!) for a 6 point lead at half-time.

The Squirrel knew what deltiologists collect: 9-6 again.  And round 7 was a bit of a disaster fro the Lion: 9-2, though two of their questions weren't known to either side.  The second individuals loomed and these fell perfectly for the Squirrel: 13-2 and an unassailable lead.  The Squirrel took the last two rounds as well for a convincing result (albeit with a following wind from the balance of the questions).

The Lions took the beer leg 18-17.
The score was actually 90-59, sounds a little better to me.  :)  Congrats Squirrel, only one team and one individual question incorrect.

A super game in which the lead changed hands five times, the superior experience of The Bell telling in the end. The lead would have been greater had the captain not taken the joker on the golf question - then fouled it up. The beer leg doesn't count in this occasion, but I am going to mention it as we got all 20, and we haven't done that very often.

The Hen was never able to take the lead in this match and the Bell always seemed to have that little extra in reserve.  The Bell also tellingly out-bonused their hosts 6-3 although honours were even in both individual rounds.

RLB won the toss and took the 'B' questions.  After two rounds, RLB lead 14-16.  Both teams did not fare well on the first individual round!  It went 0-5 to RLB.  With RLB taking the next two rounds 6-8 and 6-9, the score was 26-38 at half time.
The next two rounds went 4-8 then 2-6.  Sugar Loaf edged another low-scoring second individual round 6-5, making the score 38-57.  RLB continued the form with 6-7, 2-8 scores in the last two rounds.  Final score 46-72 to Red Lion B.
Sugar Loaf took some comfort with a 15-14 win in the beer leg.

R1 - 8 all.
R2, we snuck ahead by one but should have been more bar an administrative error on Stanley Baldwin.  R3 a gap opened up as we took it 10-6 but the Bell definitely had the rougher set of questions. We extended in R's 4 and 5 with only a hiccup on Boston v Phoenix - half time was 42-30.
R6 fairly even, we got as far as Kevin Mc but couldn't grasp the Guire and R's 7, 8, and 9 were flattering but exposed gaps in our knowledge of political siblings. Final score 84-52 but felt closer.
Beer leg - just a bit of fun, not part of the main quiz - was 17 to 12.

The Plough were suffering because two of their regulars had opted to attend a different cup competition involving a local team playing at Aston Villa.  Their substitutes included a certain Pete Oxbrow, who has occasionally played for the Squirrel in previous seasons, leading to occasional cries of 'Judas!' from the spectators (Sid and Doris Bonkers).  Following close scrutiny of the transfer papers play was able to commence (slightly delayed by motor trouble in the ranks of the Squirrel.  The Squirrel lost the toss and the Plough opted to go first - a fateful decision as later transpired.

Rather surprisingly, the first round went 4-10 to the Squirrel, but normal service was resumed with a full house on round 2.  Both sides found the selection of individual questions tricky, but the questions fell much better for the Squirrel and the round went 0-13.  Apart from three more 8-8  ties, the Squirrel took every round, winning by a 31 point margin.

All agreed that the questions were heavily biased in favour of the team starting second, and this is confirmed by several other scores showing a similar margin.  The Squirrel also took the beer leg 13-17.

I've lost the scoresheet so I'm winging it here but you won't believe what the score was after Round 1. 
IT WAS EIGHT ALL!!!!! - Quite incredible.
It was also a full house in R2 but R3 saw FCSC pull ahead by 6 with RLB dropping the Olympian and the government department.
R4 saw RLB narrow the gap to 4 as FCSC missed Doncaster Racecourse but from then on  each round was a 2-4 point win to the sports club bar R9 which was a full house.
In total FCSC dropped 2 all night (Big Sleep and Mata Hari) which weren't picked up and RLB dropped 7 of which 5 were.  
Beer Leg was 18-14 to FCSC.

Yet another very close game between these teams. Hen A took the lead in round 1 taking it 9-6. Maximums were scored in the next round  before RLA took the individual round by 8-7 before Hen A stretched their lead to 33-28 by winning round 4 by 9-6. RLA took round 5 to reduce the deficit to leave the score at 37-36 to the Hen. Maximums were scored in round 6 before RLA gained the lead for the first time by  taking the next round 10-4. The second individual round went to the Hen A by 11-6 leaving the match all square at 60-60. Maximums were scored in round 9 and in the final decided on knowledge of the Eurovision song contest. The Hen A were unable to recall that Brotherhood of Man is mentioned in 'Imagine' (neither could RLA) while RLA answered the easier sistyer question correctly. Theis left the RLA to run out victors by 76-74.
Hen A then took the beer leg 17-16.

The Squirrel won the toss and went second (the worst decision of the evening, as it transpired).  The first two rounds were both full houses, but the Squirrel got their noses in front, taking the first individuals 8-9.  But the Lion came straight back taking the next 8-4.  The Squirrel took the 5th round to level the scores at half-time.

Round 6 was another full house, but the Squirrel picked up a bonus on the next round to open a 3 point lead.  The Lion took the next two rounds by the odd point, but were still trailing by a point going into the last.  But the Lion took the final round 10-4 for a clear win.

The beer leg was tied 18-18.

Going to dash this out as you wont get it before Friday otherwise.
R1 - 9-6, obviously, but R2 was 8-6 in return. We snuck a close first individuals but R4 went 10-2 our way with Lana Turner, Jill Ireland and the dogs all suiting us. 
R5 was 7 all and half time came at 42-31.
R6 was a full house and the A narrowed the gap by three before two consecutive 11-2 rounds to FCSC effectively sealed the game.
The Hen took the last 9-6 for a final score of 84-61.
There were some very lopsided questions that didn't entirely balance themselves out but we've seen worse. We dropped 4 and the Hen grabbed three rebounds, they dropped 11 and we stole 8.
Lost the beer round though 15-16.

Both the teams from the hotbed of quizzing excellence that is The Bell now have one win from their last seven league matches. But it's Bell B that is on the up after a deserved win. The first round was 7-7. which is novel, then two rounds each saw Bell B 36-31 up at half time. Bell A pulled that back to level and were actually five points up half-way through the second individual round. Then we (OK, I) didn't get Stoke City, they did, six-point swing to Bell B, game over.

The Squirrel returned to form and lost the toss, so the Hen were faced with perhaps the key decision of the evening and opted to go first.  It may be that wasn't a good choice, in any event the questions fell well for the Squirrel, who only dropped two all evening.  Interestingly (for a sufficiently small value of 'interesting') this was the first time The Squirrel have played this season in a game that has not been an away win :).

The general consensus was that the questions were a little easier (and thus, from our point of view, worse) than last week - with  perhaps too many old chestnuts.

The Hen took the beer leg by virtue of better knowledge of first wives.

On many evenings, the Bell's 73 points would have secured a victory but not tonight as the Hen A achieved what is probably their highest ever score, dropping just two questions all night.  The first round of the individuals saw each side score maximum points and until round 5 it was very close.  The away team played truer to form in the beer round which ended 18-18.  The Hen A were missing their captain, Steve someone or other, but you when you have players like Jon F to step in...

No Captain Keith so Barryowen stepped in.
Good scores all round. Three missed; Walter Scott where he was on the shortlist, Newport where we had Fairport,and Polythene Pam where we are still none the wiser.

Some real gimme's and the individuals still feel terribly easy.

Beer leg was 18-16.

Game of two halves!  Harte & Magpies B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  They won the first half 34-42, only dropping one question.  Fortunes were reversed for the second half - Sugar Loaf won that half 46-27 dropping only one question, the last one.  Only three questions not answered throughout, one was 'Orrible Ives...

And only one question missed by both teams in the beer round, Bobby Charlton of all people!  Sugar Loaf won it 18-17.

We thought these were a good set (and the final score didn't influence this view in any way :).  The questions were balanced between the teams with a good mix of more straightforward and more challenging questions, and the individual rounds weren't more difficult than the team ones.

(And the 'Birds' individual pair didn't give rise to any disputes.)

A match which Harte B deserved to win, and duly did. 33-31 to Bell A at half-time became 53-60 after the second individual. Nobody got many points in the last two rounds. Beer leg brought some respite, we got them all apart from Richard II, which Harte B did get. Still no home wins in the league at The Bell this season.

No Captain Keith so Barry Owen stepped into the fray with great aplomb despite being thrown the scraps in the two individuals.
7 all in round one was followed by a full house before the first individuals saw us pull out a 6 point lead. By half time the lead was 8 points.
R7 suited no one but went 4-3 to the club but another good individual round of 12-4 effectively sealed the game. 
Two challenging rounds saw a final score of 81-52.

We feel that the questions are still finding their way and went from being insultingly easy at the start of the season  to more challenging and interesting, but also more unbalanced. Every match seemed to have a quite one sided last round last week but we thought tonight's were pretty damned good.

Plough won the beer leg 16-15 with FCSC crossing out Yahoos at the last minute.

We're two points down, three questions to go
A ray of hope! Sounds like they don't know
Get the last two right and we'll just scrape home.
This came to pass, thanks to Johnny Mathis.

Always a hard-fought fixture, the Squirrel won the toss (first one this year!)  and elected to put the FCSC in first.  The first round was the, by now traditional, full house.  Round 2 was a bit of a disaster for The Squirrel who went down 4-10, due to a 3-pointer on Cheddar Gorge/Wookey Hole and lack of knowledge of London classified ad web sites.  This is a big lead for anyone to give the champions - could The Squirrel come back from this early setback?    Superior knowledge of musicals gave the Squirrel a 3-point edge on the first individual round and they also took the 4th round 8-6, narrowing the deficit to one point.  But the FCSC struck back to take the 5th round 6-8 for a 3-point lead at half-time.

Honours were even on rounds 6 and 7, so it was into the second individuals with The Squirrel still trailing.Scoring on James Bond Themes and Terriers saw the Squirrel take it 10-5 and a 2-point lead for the first time.  Round 9 was another tie, so it was all down to the final round.  Alas for The Squirrel, they failed to identify Johnny Mathis as the Olympian and UK Xmas number 1 singer, while the FCSC confidently picked up the bonus.  Full points on the remaining questions saw the FCSC finish victors by a single point.  A real battle, and both teams were pleased with their performances, tinged with regert for what might have been on The Squirrel's side.

The Squirrel recovered for a perfect score on the beer leg, taking it 20-18.

On a warm summer evening there?s no better place to be than Penn Street.  You can sit outside The Squirrel with a pint of bitter watching the dying ember of a cricket match before the sun slides down into the Vale of Aylesbury. However, dear reader, if you return in dark of December a different contest awaits where no quarter is given by the battle hardened quartet in their quiz team. This week was no exception as they awaited the arrival of the rag tag renegades of Farnham Common Sports Club. Undefeated arrogant and vain they swaggered in as if they owned the place stake their claim on the corner table and sat waiting for the first blow. How we are allowed to progress beyond the M40 baffles most gentlefolk and once again, Alan & Nicola Morgan sat facing each other, the ever fractious Eric Harris glistened with intent and Captain Keith watched every move.

The toss was offered and the Captain called wrong; The Squirrel gave us the option to lead off.  The fuse was lit. The most titanic struggle erupted in this once genteel pub.

A mutually perfect first round disguised the impending combustion as they dropped two question and we greedily grabbed the bonus to roar into a six point lead as boots thudded into unprotected soft bits. They smashed back as the captain dropped his musical question and they ripped the bonus from our mouths and clawed back into the match. 26 -23 

The fourth round lurched to them as we dropped a question but they missed the bonus and stayed perfect.  We flung ourselves forward for a perfect round five and they stumbled and dropped one. Again we missed the bonus, the gap was three points and we faced the second individuals 54-51.

They rushed and Caledonian war cries rent the air as they gave us a battering, both Morgans fell and they swooped on the slippery bonus and surged all over us. They took the lead 59-61 with two rounds to go. 

It?s a simple equation -  if they get all of their questions right they win. They were perfect in round nine so were we 67 -69. The storm clouds gathered and the gods of quiz glared at the stand- off.

Round ten they went first and staggered. They didn?t know the Olympic hopeful, cheesy, American, middle of the road, chart topper. They said Chuck Berry, incorrect. Mr Morgan growled Johnny Mathis and the world tilted on it axis. Our question on heavy metal chart topping fencers, Bring your daughter to the slaughter Bruce Dickinson. We were ahead by one and needed to be perfect for the rest of the round. We were. 76-75 was the final score. 

Both teams slumped into their seats hardly believing the result. When tales of mighty contests are told this one will rank as one of the best. A feast was served and we went forward into the beer round. Again a battle royal but they sneaked it 18-20 by being perfect.


When we are sitting in the Great Hall of Quiz Valhalla the table next to us must be reserved for the Squirrel it would be an honour to raise our hats and glasses in their direction.

Outside the rain came down as Victoria and Nike wept tears of Joy, hats tilted at an indecent angle as we went home singing Run for the Hills. In the distance we noticed the blood red glow in the sky towards Botley. The Hen & Chickens B await next week, but that?s another day.

The Hen took the lead in the first round and never relinquished it, though they did lose Round two to the Sugar Loaves.  Both the individual rounds were quite closely contested with the Hen taking these with an aggregate score of 17-14 and noted for both teams correctly answering their Joker questions.  The esoteric dog questions drew blanks from both teams.  The Hen also won the Beer leg for the first time this season.

The first two rounds yielded a perfect 16-16, and the first individual round was also tied 7-7.  RL edged into the lead in round four, after which the score was 27-30.  They also took round 5 to open up a lead of 5 points at half-time (32-37).

On resumption, another full house round ensued, then a 7-6 win in round seven to Bell made the score 47-51 to RL, still close....RL edged the second individual round 6-9, and the difference was now 7 points.  Round nine was decisive, it went badly for Bell and was the clincher for RL, who took it 2-10 to gain an unassailable lead.  With the last round also going to RL 6-7, the final score was 61-77 in their favour, somewhat flattering!  

RL edged the beer leg 15-16, thank you Bangladesh!

This looks like a comfortable win for the away side. Analysis of the answers, however, shows that Bell A got 31 of their own questions and 8 bonuses. The Plough 30 of their own and seven of ours. Factor in that The Plough missed both of their joker questions, both picked up by the away side, and all of a sudden this could have been a lot closer. Two further notes: one, for the second week in a row, Bell A played a team that had had a player on Mastermind the previous Friday. Two, the supper was top scoff! Thank you, The Plough. Bell A won the beer leg thanks to our superior knowledge of Gaelic pastimes and English literature. That is, we got the shinty and the Shropshire lad questions.

After the customary gentle full house romp though round 1, the Red Lion took a two point  lead in round 2 when the Hen went for Cheddar Gorge instead of Wookey Hole. Back to all square in round 3 when neither mountaineer knew which country Mount Elbrus was in - wasn't it so much easier when it was all the Soviet Union. The Hen pulled ahead in rounds 4 and 5 to be 42-36 up at the interval. After a 7-7 draw in round 6 the Hen went three points further ahead in round 7. The second individuals were a bit of a disaster for the Red Lion, which they lost 4-9, including the loss of their canine joker. Despite the Red Lion pulling back a couple of points in round 9, the Hen ran out 81-69 winners.

Honours even in the beer leg which finished 18-18. Red Lion were closer on the tie break. 

As ever, a most convivial evening at the Red Lion.

Each of the first three rounds were tied, with the teams each dropping a single question.  In fact, for the first time any of us can remember, every individual question in both rounds was answered correctly.  The Squirrel took the fourth round 9-2, but lost the fifth 5-7, for a 5 point lead at halftime.  Round 6 also went the Squirrel's way 10-4 and the lead was beginning to look unassailable.  And, indeed with the difference on each of the next rounds being no more than the odd point or two, that was how it finished.  

The Squirrel just pipped the Harte on the beer leg (superior marmalade knowledge).

The gap between the two sides in this fairly evenly contested game was never more than six points but the game partly hinged on Indian cricketers and career defining roles.  A few questions stumped both teams -  the tricky cities from Slovenia and Slovakia, for example -  but, all told, only four questions went unanswered in a set which was generally considered to be pitched at an appropriate level.

Good game, good game. 
Neither side knew enough about the Europa Cup to get the Eastern European cities, Eric didn't know Erik, and The Hen made an unprofessional call on the Bodie/Doyle 50/50.
Hen had a good R4 which went 9-4 to them, R's 1, 8, 9 and 10 were all draws and the other went narrowly our way to give an 80-74 final score.  

Beer leg was 20 all which we think is a first and we all enjoyed the Groundhog question.

Beer leg was 20 all which we think is a first and we all enjoyed the Groundhog question.

Beer leg was 20 all which we think is a first and we all enjoyed the Groundhog question.

Hen & Chickens B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  After three rounds it was 26 all, the first question dropped was in round four.  35-43 to Hen at half-time.

Harte B won round seven 8-4 closing the score to 49-55, that was going to be the big comeback :), but Hen won all of the remaining rounds, end score 66-82.   Harte won questions not answered correctly 4-2 (where's that straw?).

H&CB scored a full house on the beer leg (17-20).

The end of one run, the continuation of another. For the first time this season, Bell A went second. But still no home win at The Bell this season, as again the 'away' side took the local bragging rights. The seven point lead at the finish was the largest the lead had been throughout a tight game, aided by a bonus on the last Tour de Fran?e question. The loudest cheer of the night greeted the correct guess that Helsinki is indeed the northernmost mainland European capital, us completing a clean sweep of the beer leg questions.

The Squirrel won the toss and chose to go second.  Round 1 was (as is now traditional) 8-8.  Round 2 went to the Squirrel 9-6 on the film question and so it was on to the first individuals - this was not a high-scoring round: 5-6 to the Squirrel.  Rounds 4 and 5 both went to the Squirrel, to put them 29-41 ahead at half-time.  

Round 6 was another full house, but round 7 saw the Loaves find their form to take it 9-4.  The second individuals were a bit of a disaster for the Squirrel: 5-2, reducing their lead to just 4 points.  Round 9 went to the Squirrel 6-8, as did (after much sweat) the final round.

The Sugar Loaf took the beer leg decisively 19-16.

A good day at the office for the sports club as we entertained difficult opponents from The Bell A.
Round 1 - guess what? 8 all. And so was Round 2. The first individuals saw Renoir avoid both teams before The Bell missed their joker thanks to The Kings of Leon. The Bell pulled one back but the sports club had snuck into a 6 point lead that grew to 8 after R4 as neither side knew the Book of Samuel but we fluked Judges. R5 was a full house and half time came at 42-34 to FCSC.
R6 was another full house but the club pushed the lead to 11 after the Bell tripped up over Nick Knowles.
They narrowed this to 9 after we missed Ruddigore but that went back to 11 after the Lightwater Valley pair. The question may say it's near Ripon but we all think it's on the road between Shangri La and Brigadoon as no one in the room had heard of it. Finally another full house in the last round saw the match end 83 -72.
With no team questions wrong from FCSC and only 5 from the Bell it was a very high scoring game and 72 would often be enough to see a team home.
 Lost the beer leg 19-18 as neither side knew the walking stick but the Bell got the prisoner of War camp.
Good night all round.

RLB won the toss and took the 'A' questions, not a good choice for them as it turned out.  The outcome of the match was pretty much decided on the scores in the individual rounds and in round ten.
After two rounds the scores were level at 15-15.  RLA romped the first individual round 2-14.  With round four also going to RLA 6-9 and round five tied at 8-8, RLA led 31-46 at half time.
The next two rounds went 8-8 and then 9-4 to RLB.  RLA's lead was 10 points going into the second individual round (48-58).  Again, RLA took that round 4-7, and with round nine tied at 6-6 the matched was already decided at 58-71.  RLA won the last round convincingly 3-9, making the final score 61-80.

A close beer leg, RLB taking some solace with a 19-18 win!

Just like the Squirrel in the Cup Final, the Hen also won the toss and inserted their opponents and were soon regretting the decision though Paul rescued the first round by knowing the name of the Jetson?s dog. The rest of the first half was very tight and half time arrived with the Hen holding a two point advantage. 
The second half remained a very close affair until the Hen suffered a poor round nine which meant that both teams entered the final round tied on 66 points apiece. The Hen then surprised themselves by going dormie thanks to 6 points from the first two questions but then reverted to type by getting the next two questions wrong but the Sugar Loaf fell agonisingly short by only picking up one of the bonuses. A really enjoyable and hard fought match and a big thank you to Peter for being the question master.
The Sugar Loaf got some measure of revenge by thumping the Hen in the beer leg.

Bell B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  After two rounds RLB lead 16-13.  Bell B pulled it back to 22-21 after the first individual round when RLB missed their joker.  RLB won the next two rounds however, and the score at half-time was 39-31.
Round six was low-scoring, going to RLB 4-1, Bell took round seven 6-7.  The second individual round went badly for the Bell, RLB took it 13-2, which pretty much secured the match with the scores at 62-41.  The final score was 78 - 49 to RLB.
RLB won the beer leg 19-14.

So much for the early-season promise. The Bell A slumped to a third successive league defeat. While on the one hand we could point to the score being 5-5 on bonus points and 4-4 in rounds won, fact is The Plough was the better team on the night. The key round being R8, the SD one individual. Losing that 11-4 didn't help. Oh well.

This always looked likely to be a crucial match with the Squirrel just 2 points ahead of the team in second place in the league (but with FCSC on a far superior 'goal average').  The Squirrel won the toss and elected to go second.  The first round was the traditional 8-8, but round 2 produced the only question to go unanswered by either side ('fang' - I think both sides may have over-thought it), which put the FCSC two ahead going into the first individuals.  Round 3 fell perfectly for the Squirrel who took it 6-12 for a 4-point advantage.  Rounds 4 and 5 were both full houses, so that remained the situation at half-time.

On round 6 FCSC showed their strength with better knowledge of newsreaders and Booker winners to take it 10-4 and resume their two-point lead.  The next three rounds were all maximum points (including, obviously, the second individuals), setting things up for a nail-biting last round.  The first pair were dismissed to the boundary, and the Squirrel correctly identified the TB vaccine.  Then it was the FCSC to identify the common ailment declared eliminated in the Americas during 2015.  Was it Measles?  Alas no, it was German Measles - on such close decisions are matches decided.  Neither side can remember a match in which BOTH sides scored in the 80s.

The beer leg finished an honourable 18-18 tie (both sides getting different questions wrong).  A fine match played in the best traditions of the league.

What a game.
8 all, obviously.
Then FCSC snuck ahead after both teams overanalysed Fangs but we got incisors.
First Individuals went badly for us and a two point lead turned into a four point deficit which was how it stayed to half time after two full houses.
R6 saw us try reverse swing and a 6 point win put us two up again.
R7 full house
R8 full house
R9 full house.
R10 - bloody Germans. We went for measles but Squirrel knew it was the Teutonic version to nick the game by one solitary point in 161  - the most we've ever seen.
The win gives the Squirrel a firm hand on the trophy and leaves us to concentrate on the Cup. Not quite Chelsea. more Man City.

Beer leg was 18 all.

A funny evening where neither side ever really got out of second gear. Eric's absence and knowledge of monarchs and shipping forecast areas was felt on a quiz that seemed to be based around an old man's memories of his prep school and a childhood holiday in 1954. There was also, from our side at least, some silly buggery as we slipped into Two Ronnie's territory by answering the previous question. Anyway, we scraped a win but stormed the beer leg 19-14.

Sugar Loaf won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  8-8 after round one!  SL went into a 3 point lead after round two, but RLB took the first individual round to close to score to 22-23.  The next two rounds were shared, at half-time SL lead 34-37.

Rounds six and seven were also shared, SL leading 48-52 going into the second individual round.  That round went 8-11 to SL, and with the last two rounds also going to SL 5-8 and 2-7, the final score was 63-78 to Sugar Loaf.

A close beer leg, RLB won 18-17.

The Bell was full, someone was having a birthday party in the restaurant, so just like 25 years ago we played in the bar. Which at least meant we could watch England 2 France 0 with the sound turned down. Which is relevant as this game felt very much like a pre-season friendly: we've all known each other for years and what does it matter if we get the odd question wrong? 

R1 was 8-8, but in R2 the home side did better on dollar bills and fictional doctors. We won the first individual round too, everybody knowing Tom Graveney and Lorna Doone except the poor people that were asked the question. Hen A pulled back a point in R4, we knew that tete-a-tete was wrong even though we'd had vis-vis before. R5 was 7-7 so 38-32 to The Bell at the break. 

The scores continued to climb slightly faster for The Bell in the second half also, at least until the final round which we fouled up completely, though not so completely as to dent badly the 12 point lead that we had. Final score 73-65. The beer leg was lost by a point - would have been a draw but the captain was offered Maggie Smith or Jane Fonda and went the wrong way.

The Hen won the toss and chose to answer first.  The first pair of horse racing questions, stumped everyone, but round 1 finished even on 6-6.  No-one knew that Cambridge became a city as recently as 1951, so that gave the Squirrel a 2 point lead going into the first individuals, which the Squirrel squeaked 8-7 (aided by somewhat easier questions than those for the Hen).  Round 4 was even and the Squirrel picked up a further point on round 5, giving them a 32-36 lead at the halfway mark.

The Squirrel knew Wilmington was in Delaware, which increased their lead to 7 points. but round 8 saw them miss two questions (James Bond actors' wives and Belgian surnames), narrowing the gap to 2.  The individuals produced a full house and so did round 9.  Could The Squirrel hold on?  No - they failed to connect the British fashion designer and liqueur Galliano and lost by 1 point.  (A fair result, as the Hen had the rough end of a couple of questions).

Dander thoroughly aroused, The Squirrel smashed a perfect score on the beer leg, taking it 20-17.

With Captain Keith absent Barry Owen stepped up to the mark and would have been delighted to get the team off the mark with his specialist subject of horse racing. FCSC built a lead that Bell B clawed on the first individuals but then pulled away all evening for a handsome win. It is quite clear though that the new kids on the block are a bright bunch and just need to become more familiar with how the matches work and what subjects tend to come up.
Quirky moment of the evening was when everyone in the room knew the lyrics to When I'm Sixty Four  apart from either if the two that had it as their individual question.

Finally, on behalf of all members of Farnham Common Sports Club quiz team and the wider club community in general we would like to apologise for any prehistoric, public schoolboy, Thatcher's Britain sexist behaviour displayed in last night's quiz against the Bell B.
We wholly acknowledge that in the twenty first century it should not be considered unusual for a girl to know about football and that any views expressed to the contrary do not reflect those of the club as a whole.

A game of two halves. RLB won the toss, took the 'A' set of questions and rued the decision for the opening four rounds, all won by Sugar Loaf.  RLB took the fifth round 8-6, making the half-time score 26-37.

RLB then took rounds six, seven and eight 9-6, 9-6 and 7-6 to close the gap, making the score 51-55 to Sugar Loaf.  Round nine was shared 8-8, so the difference was four points (59-63) going into the last round.  Again, there was a close finish as Sugar Loaf missed their first question of the round making it 61-63 with three questions each remaining.  An upset was avoided though with both teams answering the remaining questions correctly.  Final score 67-69 to Sugar Loaf.

The beer leg was tied at 19-19, with only two differences in the answers - it was down to George Burns v Bob Hope and Mexico v Philippines!  With one each incorrect, RL got some consolation in the tie-break!  ;)  (hic!)

A picture paints a thousand words:! https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/10221307/2014-11-18-QuizRLAvPlough.png

Plough won on the tie break on the beer round.

Plough: 24,800
RLA: 22,500
Answer: 26,000

A quirky quiz in two respects. One, the first three incorrect answers given by Bell A were the correct answer to the next question. Goodwood, Chelmsford, Ligament. Cue the famous Ronnie Barker does Mastermind sketch. Two, the match itself which changed course in the middle of round six. 
The first half was nip and tuck with few incorrect answers and only one bonus point, 37-36 to the home team at half time. At one point in round six Hen A was 42-37 up, following which The Bell A got every question right whereas Hen A got seven wrong, on six of which a bonus point was scored. Final score 81-64 to Bell A.
It may be that the concentration of at least half the Hen team was elsewhere - imminent grandparentness far more important than knowing about Jeffrey Archer novels. 
The beer leg hinged on the theatre question. We guessed The Globe, they didn't. Cokes all round!

The Lion won the toss and chose to go in first.  The first two rounds were both full houses, but on the indivduals the Lion opted for the 'could be anything' Initials questions for their joker.  Sadly for them, this was the only question not to be answered correctly, and the Squirrel picked up the bonus, giving them a 6 point advantage.  Back to the team questions, and picking up the bonus on the 'boxer named Jens' question in round 4 gave the Squirrel a 9 point lead at half time.

The Lion took a point back in round 6, and round 7 was yet another full house, but the Squirrel again managed a full house on the individuals as well as two bonuses, giving them a 14 point lead going into the penultimate round.  With both sides scoring strongly, it never looked like there was much chance of making up such a large deficit, and so it proved.

Overall we thought these were a well-balanced and relatively challenging set of questions - a good start to the new season.

As the result suggests this was a closely contested match but one in which the Hen and Chickens A held the lead in five of the rounds with the Plough ahead only once.  At one point, the H&C led by six points but their undoing proved to be second individual round in which the Plough pulled back this six point deficit to level the scores at 55 each.  The 7-1 victory for the Plough here proved decisive in ensuring an eventual draw as both the final two rounds ended in draws.  The beer round finished in a victory for the visitors by 18-15.

Having their first game in the league Bell B had to play most of the first half with only 3 players.  Sugars took an early lead and never really looked back winning every round and coming out winners 76 to 36.  Good luck to Bell B I am sure they will do a lot better once they get used to the kind of questions set.

Sugars also won the beer round 17-9

Not one of Keith's classic reports but I'll give you the basics.
Unable to remember the very forgettable estelle Morris FCSC found themselves 9-6 down at the end of Round 1 but from then on snuck a point or two in each round to secure a comfortable 85-70 win. 
Between the two teams only one question went unanswered all evening which was the Uruguay one - still not convinced, I'll look it up in a minute.
Highlights were Eric's unfailing knowledge of ancient English monarchs and Keith's ability to pluck obscure railway stations from the depths of his memory.
FCSC won the beer leg as well to make it an enjoyable and affordable start to the new season.

Once again the perennial champions Hen B came a cropper at the hands of their bogey team at The Bell.
39-40 to the Hen at half time - only one question not answered by either side, Hen essentially leading at that point by two bonus questions to one. That became 57-53 after round seven. The Bell retook the lead and then immediately lost it during the individuals and went into the last round trailing 67-71. 
The Bell struck lucky with the gymnasts but knew the cricketers, 70-71. We are also pretty useful on who was king of England at what date, even when the question is disguised by a couple of obscure battles. 73-71. Four questions answered correctly and that left The Bell ahead by two points at the gong. 
Just to show that this was not a complete fluke, the beer leg went to the home side as well.

This game was notable for both  some challenging questions (and largely balanced ones, too) and its closely-contested nature.  Indeed, both sides were tied at 48 all at the end of round eight but both the finals two rounds went to the Hen and so will appear in the final of the plate for the second year running.  The Hart had a clean sweep in the beer round.

So it's "eyes down; look in" for a new season, with a new question setter.  Round 1 ended 7-7 (for a change!), but the Loaf picked up a bonus on round 2 to take the lead.  Individuals were 10-10, and the Squirrel struck back on round 4, but missed the bonus (picking the wrong one between Morpeth and Alnwick).  We also guessed wrong on the cigarettes (Marlborough or Camel?), which left the Loaf 4 up at half-time.

Round 6 was a full house, but the Squirrel slipped up on Catweazle, to fall 7 behind.  The second individuals were also 10-10 (can't remember the last time that happened) and round 9 was a further full house.  Despite managing to pull back a couple of points on the last question of the evening, The Sugar Loaf ended deserving winners by a 5 point margin.

The Squirrel took their revenge on the beer leg, though!

4-7 after R1, which makes a change, before Bell had the better of the rest of the first half to take a 36 -34 lead.
Second half saw that turned around by FCSC to come home 76-67.
That's very brief so that I can give our view of the new questions. Overall, more challenging and interesting and less predictable than before but with some that were too easy. The view was that the team that went second in each half had noticably the harder set which is fine as long as yin equals yang.
Not really seen enough to comment on the individuals yet.
Beer leg was 14.5 - 15 to FCSC. It's complicated.

The first Chiltern league match at the Harte and Magpies, appropriately between the two home teams!  Our thanks to Steve, landlord of the Harte and Magpies for welcoming us to our new home.  Both teams were a regular player short, through injuries, sorry - holidays...

HMB won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  After losing the first round, they lead 12-13 after round two. HMA missed the joker on the first individual round, and with the next two rounds going 7-5, then 4-8, HMB lead 27-34 at half time.

The next two rounds went to HMA - the score closed to 40-41 going into the second set of individuals.  Both jokers were scored (on English geog), and with some luck on Norse mythology, HMB took the round 7-4, so the lead opened to 4 points in favour of HMB. With round nine going to HMA 8-6, the last round was a tense affair!  HMA actually lead 59-58 going into the last question pair, but the result went to HMB (Massachusetts!), a close run thing!

HMB won the beer leg 14-18.

A tentative response on just one set of questions: a good mix of questions, pitched at an appropriate level - but with, in this set, a disproportionate number relating to Africa - though our Africa expert was quite happy! The absence of any first round 'gimme' questions was a positive feature.

It is also perhaps too early to raise the matter of the absence of any questions on Fulham .

A frustrating game for The Squirrel, which saw the rub of the green go with the 'A' questions all the way through.

The first round was as round 1 generally is, but round 2 saw the Sugars ease ahead with the Squirrel unable to come up with 'cola' as the Spanish for 'tail'.  A failed tussle with marmalade in round 3 made the Squirrel's situation still stickier, but the Sugar's puzzle over monkeys in round 4 left the scores 39-36 at the break to the home side.

The second half saw the Sugars gradually ease away, with a full house in 3 rounds to the Squirrel's 1.  The gradual and soul-sapping erosion was punctuated by the bizarre mis-match of category and questions in the last pair of individuals:  'Places named after people' with the answers being films?  Passingly odd, but rather symptomatic of an apparently carelessly put together set of questions.   The upshot of all this was an 80-68 victory for the Sugar Loaf.

The beer leg was a 17-all tie.

With Captain Keith absent Barry Owen stepped off the bench for a dry run of the impending cup final.
Unbelievably after the first round the score was eight all but FCSC went the wrong way on the Boca Jnrs v River Plate call to see the Bell pull a three point lead out at the end of R2.
We then dropped our first two individual questions with bonuses being picked up to see us 7 down half way through R3 but the Bell missed their joker and the next question to put us two points up after R3.
R4 was a full house and neither side knew tartaric acid bringing a half time score of 39 - 35.
The second half was a more uneven affair with the club picking up bonuses on the Cairngorms, Disney films, that well known place named after Sir James Thecryinggame, homophones, Mickey Rourke, Don Quixote and the Isle of Wight.
Only a daft call on the joker by your author, mixing up Disney Mice with Disney Fairies, put a dent on a solid performance that was made to look shinier than it perhaps deserved by as lopsided a set of questions as we have had this season.
Beer leg was a tie at 17 all.

Rather like last week - close for four rounds. Full houses in rounds 1 and 2. Plough go two points up in round 3. Hen get one pack in round four and then everything changes. Hen win round 5 by 10-2 and then win every round in the second half to run out 81-52 winners. 

Plough definitely had the rough end of the questions - and what was all that nonsense about places named after people?

Beer leg was 18-14 to the Hen.

The Red Lion A team won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  The first round was tied 8-8, then B's won round two 9-6 and held the lead after the first individual round 23-22.  RLA took round four 6-9 and did not lose the lead thereafter, they lead by 7 points at the interval (33-40).

RLA took round six 6-9, round seven was tied 8-8.  With the last three rounds also going to RLA 6-9, 4-8, and 3-9, they recorded an emphatic win, the final scores being 60-83.

RLA won the beer leg 17-18.

The Squirrel lost the toss, but since the Bell opted to go first, it made no difference :)

The first two rounds were a (very easy) full house.  The first individuals revealed the first weakness -neither side knew which Henry had reigned the longest.  Round 4 was a problem for the Squirrel, 4-9 and a 7 point lead to the Bell.  Pulling back 3 points on the 5th round left the Squirrel with a 4 point deficit at halftime.

After another full house, the Bell took the 7th round by knowing the current Transport Minister.  The second individuals also proved a problem for the Squirrel: 3-7 leaving them trailing by 11 points, which remained the gap at the final whistle.

The Bell rubbed salt into the wound taking the beer leg by the odd point.
It was a a little one sided but I hope that doesn't put LoL off as it was lovely to see them back and I hope they return again next year in at least one form of the game.
Despite what we all thought was a fairly tough set (good!), the questions fell well for The Squirrel (apart from me blowing my individual on sports retailers), resulting in a comfortable victory.
There were several unbalanced pairs (we thought) but nevertheless we were soundly thrashed. Our title bid seems to have floundered this season!! Oh well, there's always the cup!

A topsy turvy match in which The Plough started strongly opening up a 7 point lead after 2 rounds.H&M then proceeded to win the next 6 rounds and lead 54-48. Plough missed both Joker questions on Aussie PMs and American Football.However, the home team finished with a flourish taking the final rounds 9-2 & 7-4 to complete a narrow victory in what was a tense but enjoyable contest played in a good spirit.H&M won a close beer leg 17-16.

Harte & Magpies B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  The first round was a full house, but after that Sugar Loaf won all of the rounds apart from the first individual round (9-6) and round ten (5-4).
The half time score was 31-37.  Sugar Loaf had big wins in rounds seven and nine, end score was 56-77.

Sugar Loaf also took the beer leg 15-17.  I need a beach....

The CQL Duckworth Lewis method has been dusted off for the first time this season as the Bell B were not able to make the game and so both scores have been entered on the average of the last three matches. Not ideal but rules is rules.

Just for laughs the Morgans played The Rest of the World and won 64 - 43.
I won the beer leg - Hoorah!

Once again the final scoreline does not do justice to a fascinating and hard fought match.  The Squirrel usually pride themselves on their performance in the individual rounds, but they were both a bit of a disaster: 4-12 & 3-11.  Fortunately, we were able to make up the difference on the team rounds, but carrying just a 3 point lead into the last round did not make for a comfortable finish.

This was a very closely contested match throughout and though the Hen led for most of it, the margin was never more than three points.  The Harte timed their surge to perfection and finally took the lead in round 9 by two points only for them to fail to score in the last two questions.  Had their knowledge of Chinese geography been marginally less poor than that of the Hen, it would have been a different story.

Bell A started well, and if we had stuck with our first choice (Wab) rather than our second (Woy) we would have had a clean sweep of the first half. Even so, we went onto the break 45-30 to the good. Harte A recovered well in the second half, not enough to recover the league game deficit but they carried that form into a deserved win in the beer leg.

A challenging evening musically, acoustically and thermally saw a tight first half end in a flattering win for the sports club against a Sugars that were missing Colin.
A slight lead in the first two rounds was cancelled out after a couple of surprising misses in the individuals and two nip and tuck rounds in 4 and 5 saw us go in to the break, accompanied by some banging technogrime, with a 36-35 lead.
R6 was level pegging but The Sugars had a mare in R7  and we went in to the second individuals with an 11 point lead.  
With hindsight we allocated them poorly but the damage was limited to just a one point loss - flowers proved challenging for both teams. R8 was a draw and a tough last round saw a final score of 73-62.
Beer leg was a close 17-18 call and ultimately came down to a win secured by a cheetah - how often do you hear that in a quiz.

Hi All
We fielded a full team with Mark?s friend Leo stepping in at the eleventh hour but, I?m afraid, we got squarely beaten last night at the Bell.  :)
We were 3 points down at half time (28 to 31) and 14 points down at the end (48 to 62) after a complete wipeout in round 9!
Alli played a blinder and got 2 lots of joker points on her individual rounds.
We narrowly lost the beer match 13 to 14.
