Tim C (Hen and Chickens B)

Following last weeks nail-biter, a close result was to be expected and the match did not disappoint.  After a full house on the first round, the Sugars took an early lead, but the individuals went against them, putting the Squirrel ahead.  The Sugars took round 4 and round 5 was another full house, leaving the Squirrel in the lead by a single point at the halfway mark.

The Squirrel took round 6 and the next was another full house, so it was time for the second individuals, which went to the Sugars, leaving the Squirrel ahead by 2.  The next round went to the Squirrel and the last was another full house, giving the Squirrel revenge for their defeat in the cup.  The beer leg was an honourable tie.

We felt the questions were of a good standard and reasonably balanced.  A possible criticism is that the individuals were, if anything, more difficult than the team questions.

A close run match with the Hen leading most of the match. The Plough did not lie down though and almost caught the home team up in the final rounds. The Hen lost the important quiz (the beer leg) but with forthcoming battles against the FCSC and the Hen A among others, a second win in a row must surely have the visitors quaking in their boots!

Two close victories for FCSC in the first two rounds were more than cancelled out by the first individuals where we gave the Bell or joker bonus for them to take a one point lead. However R's 4 & 5 were 8-4 and 10-2 wins to put the match firmly our way. 
Half time - 38-27.
Two full houses in 7 &  8 were followed by an excellent 10-8 win before standards plummeted with a 4-3 win in round 9 but both teams saw the game out with a full house.
Indicative of the high standards we all adhere to in South Buckinghamshire was that no one knew Bargain Booze, but no one knew the Nobel Prize winners either.
Good questions, much more fun.

Beer leg was 19-15. A Comedy of Errors!

Harte & Magpies B won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  The B team spin on this is that they lost the first round 4-10, then won the rest of the match!  Strange scoring - the first individual round was a full house, 10-10;  the half time score was 28-39 to the H&M A, then the second individual round score was 4-2!  Final score 60-64 to H&M A.

The Beer round ended tied at 15-15 thanks to that pesky Sue Lawley!

A closely fought match - the Loaf pulled out a 10 point lead at halftime, with the Squirrel trying, but ultimately failing to claw their way back in the second half.  The unfortunate repetition of questions was dealt with by using the first 8 from the beer leg as the questions for round 7 - not balanced, but since it was 8-8 it didn't affect the result.

The Loaf also took the beer leg 15-14 with their superior knowledge of 2016 bronze medallists.  (Oh for the easy days when we only won a handful of medals!)

Our solution to the repeat of the previous round's questions for the second individual round was to award each team a full set of points (10 each).  The Hen extracted a measure of revenge for last week's defeat against the Plough and led throughout - though the lead was reduced to just two points for the final round.  We thought the questions were of a good standard, challenging and interesting on occasion.  The only real mismatch was the question on prisons - naming a second S. African prison was always going to be a challenge.  The musical instruments questions and the Alpine geography ones drew blanks from both teams but they were equally difficult.  The Hen also took the Beer round by 19-15, fumbling only the question on women's underwear...

We wanted more challenging questions and Fokine hell we got them but while we may have winced occasionally overall it made for a better quiz. Five questions overall went unanswered but several provoked some debate and for probably the first time this year went went into the second hour.
After an even start FCSC built a nine point lead by the second individuals - more later - but a 10-4 win for H&M in R9 made for some squeeky bum time in R10 which saw us home by three points.
Cut to the chase - Round 8 - a round that will live in infamy. We chose to ignore it and so have posted a final score of 65-62 but if we went ten points each that would be 75-72, or we could use the score from R7 which would be 72-69, or you could take an average from all the other rounds which would be 72.2222 - 68.88888, or you could take a rolling average of all previous individual rounds and on a rolling average basis amortise that blah blah blah...........
You can sort that one out Peter.
   
Beer leg was 17-14.

A match which was going comfortably in the direction of the Sports Club, who had an 8 point lead after Round 7. When, suddenly, chaos ensued. Initial reaction - "ANOTHER set of questions on SI units - why isn't Nigel here?" - then realisation that they were duplicates. What to do? 10 each? Try and select paired questions from beer round? Take the average from the other rounds? Call in a UN negotiation team? In the end we skipped the round, muttering darkly about our last chance to close the gap having just disappeared. We then proceeded to nearly close the gap. But not quite. In the beer round we got the right Louis, but the wrong farm animal, and so lost that as well.

It seems as if everybody has done something different in coping with the duplicate questions foul-up. As our question-master had already discovered the duplication at half-time, we had already used the first pair of spares in round 7. After some discussion, we played the questions that were left in round 8 as team questions. A shame as otherwise a good quiz, so slightly spoiled. Whether Harte B would h?ve got back into th ematch, we shall never know, but they were deprived of the chance, for sure. Bell won the beer leg 19-16. Yes, we had the wrong Louis as well. "I've got better things to do than wander around Europe remembering my bloody number" as I'm fairly sure was in a later Monty Python sketch.

Our workaround to the infamous Round 8 was to use the 4 spare questions as a pair of 'Pick Your Subject' subjects: 2 on Sports and 2 on Heads of State.  Each team split into two pairs, and each pair of the team took one subject.  Luckily the result of the round did not impact the final result, so even if the whole round is disallowed, the final result is still a win for the Hen.


Bob

From our point of view, these were a vastly superior set of questions, with a number of them really testing the teams.  It will be interesting to see comments from the rest of the league, but we'd really like this level of strength to be maintained.  There was only one 'full house' round during the quiz, whereas on last week's questions theer were half a dozen of them.

Two full houses in R1 and R2 followed by just one question dropped in the first set of individuals and we all feared the worst but from then on   today's more challenging questions felt like the good old days were back.
A 9 point half time lead for FCSC dropped back to 6 before we pulled away over the next four rounds and only some dumbass debate by your author stopped us getting our best score of the season so far.
Neither team knows anything about New Zealand.

A last minute switch from Medina to Mecca by the sports club, coupled with a last minute switch from Mecca to Medina by the Harte saw them nick the beer leg 18-17.

A very closely fought match with The Plough taking the lead for the first time going in to Round 9 56-54 ahead.Round 9 proved decisive as questions on Tennis, Pop Music & Politicians fell nicely for the home team who also picked up 3 bonuses for a round score of 9-2.Hen hit back in the final round 7-4 but The Plough held on.The Beer Leg was also a tight affair with The Plough edging it 20-19, Medina being the difference.

That's more like it! Good spread of questions, bonus points, plenty of laughs and an away win for Bell A.  Let's face it, we don't win at home. Possibly a good toss to win (again) and Bell A were always ahead. Our customarily feeble last round, the only one that Hen A won, didn't matter this week as by then the match was put to bed and cuddling its teddy-bear. Man of the match awarded to the bloke who got "zebras". 19-17 to The Bell in the beer leg, we missed out on the horse disease question - should have paid more attention to the Misses Pullein-Thompson.

The Bell won the toss and went first.  The Squirrel took an early lead (wartime aircraft) 9-6 and the second was a full house.  The individuals (a challenging set, we thought) went to the Bell 6-9 to level the scores.  The Squirrel took the next 9-6 and the fifth round was another full house, leaving the scores 40-37 at half-time.

Round 6 went to the Squirrel (9-6 on motoring abbreviations) and round 7 also went the Squirrel's way 7-2.  The Bell took the individuals 4-6, but still trailed by 9 points.  The last two rounds both went to the Squirrel.

The Squirrel also took the beer leg 19-13.

Very much a game of two halves.
Round 1 - 8 all, obviously.
R2 FCSC went three up but a big 11-4 win in the individuals followed by 10-4 in R4 opened a big lead that got slightly bigger by the end of R5 and a half time score of 46-27.
The second half though was a mote even affair with The Plough taking it 35-29 and winning the first three rounds with the last two drawn. 
We talked ourselves out of a couple and dropped more questions in the second half tonight than the last thee matches combined  but The Plough played very well and got some belters.
Beer leg was 17 all.

A welcome return to form by Bell A, or a blip helped by winning the toss, depending on your point of view. First half Bell A rattled up an impressive 46 points, getting all their questions correct (maybe for the first time, memory fails but that doesn't happen very often). Red Lion B missed five, three of which including the joker being picked up for bonuses. The second half was not so impressive, although five points on the Monopoly questions kept the ship afloat in the second individual round. Second half Bell A missed seven but RLB only picked up one of them (Brazil). RLB missed seven (sorry, including all four in the individuals!) and three of those were picked up. Bell A pipped the beer leg, our Len Hutton and Botswana having the advantage of their maul. Maul? Who knew? Not us.

The Plough won the toss and elected to go second, which may have been a miscalculation as they did seem to get the rough end of the questions. Hen B won round 1 by one point, round 2 by four points and round three by one point before two full house rounds left them 40-34 up at the interval. Round 6 was a low scoring 5-3 win for the Hen with round 7 a rather more decisive 9-2 win. The Plough pulled back one point in the second individuals, a round in which both teams lost their joker questions, before the Hen won  the last two rounds 7-6 and 7-2.

Revenge for the Plough in the  beer leg which they won 19-18.

A close game throughout, Bell took the lead after round one by 1 point, maintained that lead to round four (26-25) and took round five 9-4 to lead 35-29 at half time.

Red Lion edged three of the next four rounds and Bell lead again by 1 point going into the last round (55-54).  Red Lion took the lead for the first time in the last round, winning it 2-6 and so winning the match 57-60.

From RL point of view, we found the quiz a tad over sporty!  What with Rugby pipe smokers, rugby duel internationals, rugby grounds, tennis players, football MOTD, football Man City, football managers with Scottish town names, horse racing railway stations, superbike champions .... some of us don't mind, others asked me to mention it!

How ironic that there should be a round in the Individuals called Snatching Defeat from the Jaws of Victory as that is very nearly what happened in the last two rounds of today's Cup Final.
11 up with two rounds to go we hit a combination of an inspired Peter Jones and subjects we don't love to lose 6 points in round 9 and another three at the start of the last but we thank Ken Norton for getting us across the line.
It was a nervy evening with only one joker grabbed all night and many more wrong answers and bonuses than usual.
We were more convincing in the four way beer leg though where we grabbed an 18-15-14-13 win.

Actually it was worse than that - NO joker questions. All four were missed, never seen that before. First time we played ours on 2015 Rugby Union, knowing it would be about the World Cup, but we couldn't recall who played who in the quarter-finals. Theirs was on words, which turned out to be an obscure cycling expression. So both of them were two points to the other side. Second half theirs on pop music - lyrics from the 1980s, two points to us. Ours on lakes in Africa - sorry guys, Lake Malawi is still called Lake Nyasa in my atlas. Anyway, deserved victory for FCSC, for the second cup final in a row Bell A left thinking about what might have been.

The Loaf won the toss and opted to go first.  Unusually (for this season, anyway), the first round was not a full house - indeed the Loaf missed the first two (tricky) questions and the Squirrel picked up a bonus: 9-4.  The Loaf struck back taking the next round 6-7, so it was time for the individuals.  Both sides played their joker on 'Private Eye', but the Loaf failed to get theirs and the Squirrel picked up the bonus - the round went 8-3.  The fourth round was a full house and the Squirrel took the fifth 9-6 for a 12 point lead at halfway.

Round 6 was another full house and the Squirrel took the next 8-4 (the administrative 'capital' of Wiltshire defeating both sides).  The final individuals of this year's league proved decisive, with the Loaf again unlucky in picking their joker: 6-3 and a 19 point lead for the Squirrel.  The Squirrel took the penultimate round 9-6, but the evident strain proved too much and the last went to the Loaf 4-9.

Honours were shared on the beer round, with the Squirrel just losing out on the tie-break.  The result means the Squirrel claim their first league title for 20 years!!

Not quite the usual end of season showdown at the Red Lion, with both teams two regulars down because of holidays, and Red Lion A a player down.

RLB won the toss and took the 'A' questions.  Scoring was low, the first team 'full houses' coming in the fourth and fifth rounds, after which RLB lead 23-27.

More moderate scoring ensued, but RLB took the second individual round 5-9 to open up a 7 point lead at 38-45.  The last two rounds went one to each side, RLB running out winners 48-58.

RLB edged the beer leg 14-15 (thanks Gromit!).

For the second week in a row, Bell A suffered a thumping defeat - despite actually winning the team questions. But if you lose the two individual rounds 22-8, you aren't going to win many matches. Only one team question was unanswered - nobody had ever played the Atari game with a caterpillar and mushrooms. Whilst writing - well done to The Squirrel, and thanks to everyone for taking part in another fun season of league matches. Now on the the cup finals - for which I imagine that after another league double over Bell A, FCSC will be quietly confident.

No guinness, no chips and a question about their own team captain, but we had our revenge.
On the busiest night in The Bell's memory a noisy pub saw what was actually a close fight bar the two individual rounds.
8 all after R1, obviously, The Bell won the team rounds by three points but lost the individuals 9-4 and 13-4 although we all felt they were hard done by on 'fortune favours the brave' vs 'nothing ventured, nothing gained'.
Final score was 81-68 and a result that sees us have to come back next year to reclaim the title from The Squirrel to whom we offer our congratulations.

Beer leg was 17 all despite the barney about the lion.

Two surprises here. First, matches between these two teams are usually very close affairs which was not the case here. Secondly, round 1 did not end in an 8-8 draw. 

Hen B won round 1 by 9-6. Round 2 was a 7-7 draw before Hen B won the next three rounds to be 41-29 up at the interval. Hen B could only manage 5 on round 6 but sadly Red Lion A could only muster 1 point. Hen B won round 7, Red Lion A round 8 by one point, Hen B round 9 by one point and Red Lion B round 10 also by one point.

Glad to say that all the individual subjects were what they said on the tin.

Beer leg finished 18-18 with Hen B scraping by on the tie break. Peter Jones and Eric Harris, who were spectating, also scored 18 and were in fact closest on the tie break.

Another very convivial evening.

The closest of games, the teams stayed within three points of each other throughout.  After two rounds 16-16.  RLB took the lead after the first individual round 22-25, at half time, they lead 37-38.
Round six proved problematic for both teams - RLB won it 1-3!  LDS took round seven 7-6 to bring the difference down to two points, 45-47.  RLB narrowly edged the second individual round 5-6 to push the lead up to three points once more!  Round nine was tied at 8-8, so the score was 58-61 going into the last round.  LDS leveled the match on question 1 of the round (a bonus on the 'coat hanger'), and it stayed level to the end with the final score being 67-67...
But this is a plate match, the extra questions were used - 2-2!  So to the first four of the beer round - finally a result! 3-4 to RLB, LDS had an incorrect answer to 'Spanish for William' - even that was close, just a few letters missing!  Of course, the beer leg was tied with the remaining 16 questions, 14 apiece... 
Overall, a thoroughly enjoyable evening, we did encourage the Le De Spencers to join up!

The run of the questions favoured the Squirrel (the Bell won the toss and went in first).  A good performance by the Squirrel on the first set of individuals established a clear lead, which they never relinquished, despite a significant stumble on the second individuals.

The Squirrel took the beer leg with a full house (to the Bell's 19).

Three down after the first question we managed to claw it back for a three point half time lead. The second individuals opened up an 11 point gap which was 13 by the last round and 16 at the end.
Easter European drugged up athletes and Greek  fellas proved elusive, Magic Moments and Hazard were dazzling highlights, and overall a good game despite the familiarity of some of the questions.
We won the beer leg too which doesn't count but makes for a good night.

The match went according to the form book but the Hen led at half-time by 38 to 35 only to fall away, especially in the latter rounds.  The Squirrel snapped up the bonus points which came their way and finally took decisive control after the second individual round.  A measure of revenge was achieved for the Hen in the beer leg.

The Squirrel won the toss, and opted to go second.  The Hen struck immediately, taking the first round 9-4.  The second round was a full house, but the Squirrel took the individuals 6-10, narrowing the Hen's lead to a single point.  But the Hen won round 4 9-6 and although the Squirrel had a one point margin on the fifth round, they were still 3 behind at the halfway mark.

The Squirrel took round 6 9-4, to get their noses in front for the first time.  Round 7 was another full house, so it looked like the individuals would be a significant factor.  In fact, the Squirrel took them 9-5 to establish a 6 point lead.  Further advances in the last two rounds saw the Squirrel emerge victorious by 12 points, after a hard fought match.

The Hen took the beer leg, with the aid of specialised knowledge of NYC hospitals.

This top of the table clash was always going to be close and in the end it came down to the very last question.
R1 - 8 all
R2 - 8 all
R3 - we pull out a 3 point lead as Keith gets his own and a bonus with all other round drawn. 26-23
R4 - Keith to the fore again as his knowledge of pantomimes pulls another three points out. 35-29
R5 - Neither side know their battles but The B grab Pakistan while we call wrong on on Rwanda vs Tanzania. 
Half time is 39-35
R6 - Oh bum. CS Forester, Piquet and Gilbert & Sullivan all sip by to see The B take the lead 42-43.
R7 - Full House
R8 - 9 all
R9 - we pick up a bonus on Lapine but miss our own and then get suckered by Prunella Scales to see The B enter the final round three up at 64-67.
R10- It's  squeaky bum time as The B go for Capricorn and we pick up the bonus and our own question. Level pegging.
Question 2 and no one knows their potatoes. Still level.
Question 3 and both teams know their musicians. Still level.
Last question. Neither team gets Tuxedo Junction but we filled up our Little Brown Jug to won the tightest of games by 2 points.

Well played The B, wouldn't want to do that every week.
Lost the beer leg 18-17.

RLB won the toss, took the 'A' set of questions, Plough lead 14-16 after two rounds, and with a below-par first individual round, the scores were level at 20-20.  It was still close at half time, when Plough led 32-34.

The lead was five points going into the second individual round.  This turned out to be a clincher for Plough as RLB only scored on their 'singers' joker (BTW, who else answered Derby County? :) and the lead increased to ten points, 46-56.  More lowish scoring ensued, and the game ended 54-65 to the Plough.

Plough also took the beer leg 16-17.
Another dismal performance by Bell A, albeit possibly not helped by winning the toss. We lost by 16 points overall, but only 4-6 on bonus questions.

The Lion went first and the Squirrel took an early lead 9-6.  Round 2 was a full house (after some confusion about the 'wrong' first pair of questions, both sides agreed that the other would have got the right answer had the questions been more correctly phrased).  The lion took the first individuals to level the scores, but the Squirrel shaded rounds 4 and 5 for a 3 point lead at half-time. 

The Squirrel had a strong round 6, taking it 9-4, but the Lion struck back taking round 7 3-9, leaving them behind by only 2 points.  But the second set of individuals fell the Squirrels way, and they took it 11-5.  Round 9 was tough for both sides, but the Squirrel came out ahead 4-2, for a 10 point lead.  This proved too much for the Lion, as the Squirrel also took the last round for a slightly flattering 16 point margin.

Both sides agreed that these had been a good, tough set of questions, marred by a bad pair in the second round.  The beer leg was an honourable draw at 17-17.

The first three rounds saw the Red Lion A and the Sports Club score perfect rounds before The A dropped Austrian Succession in Round 4 and FCSC called badly on a 50/50 between Nelson and Churchill in R5.
This brought an interval score of 40 all in what was either a dazzling display of quizzing or an indication of overfriendly questions.
Round 6 saw The A pull out a 3 point lead as the sports club got confused between Belgium and Germany which they held through the second individuals but the final two rounds stepped up the degree of difficulty and saw a ten point swing to the club and bring a final score of 72-79.
Gilbey, Express, Lady Jane Grey Grey and Portland all saw bonuses picked up to give  a flattering scoreline while all concerned were relived the match didn't rest on the difference between Swizzles and Swizzlers.

We won the beer leg too - 18/16 again.

A very tight match throughout.

Neither team dropped any team questions in the first half - indeed it was not until round 9 that a team question went completely unanswered.Both teams dropped two questions each in round 3 with the Hen managing to eke out a single point lead by virtue of picking up two bonuses to the Bell's one. 40-39 to the Hen at half time. 

The Hen won round 6 by 10-4 but that advantage was immediately wiped out when the Bell won the next round by 9-3. All square in the second individuals so 62-61 to the Hen at that point. The Hen managed to scrape through a low scoring round 9 by 4-1 so the score was 66-62 to the Hen at that point and still anyone's game. The Bell managed to pull back just one point in the last round so a final score of 71-68 to the Hen.

After that a drawn beer leg of 18-18 seemed appropriate.

The Bell A's challenge to the hegemony of The Big Three seems to have faltered, with this narrow defeat to Hen B following a heavier loss to FCSC last week. All the team questions in the first half were answered correctly, so four rounds of 8-8. The individual round saw bonuses being swapped on TV and autobiographies, the one-point difference being that neither individual knew much about the birth of Genghis Khan. Opera was, of course, a five-pointer for Jon, though to be fair Seville better known an Nuremburg when it comes to operas naming cities. The second half saw more points being dropped, nobody knows anything about newspaper editors or sweet manufacturers. A good match, in the final analysis the Hen B was always a few points in front.

A game of two halves.  The first two rounds were full houses and the individuals were also tied.  The Squirrel squeaked rounds 4, leaving them 2 points in the lead at half-time.  

Round 6 was a further full house - it seemed the match might end in an 85-all draw.  But round 7 revealed weaknesses in the areas of the press and spelling, and the Squirrel took it 4-10.  The individuals were a bit of a disaster for the Bell ending 0-9, and the Squirrel also took the last two rounds to end with a very flattering 57-83 margin.

The Bell struck back to take the beer leg 18-17.

If there was ever a game of two halves this was it.
The first two rounds went 9-6 and 6-8 but the absence of Captain Keith and the inability to grab hold of Perry Shakes Drayton rattled the club who went down 10-4 in the individuals missing the food and drink bonus to boot. In a mild panic we then dropped the Belarussian flag and rushed Rupert Brooke to hit the halfway mark ten points down.
Round 6 was level but we narrowed the gap to 7 by the second individuals when Captain Keith arrived to watch over us with a sense of melancholic disappointment. 
Clearly the plan worked as we clawed back 6 points with inspired Bee guessing from Barry and Pinocchio from Alan.
Still one down Round 9 was tied allowing an unexpected bonus from Jim Morrison and a surprising duet from George Ezra and Ernie Tyrell to squeak home by three.
Frankly, we got away with it.

Beer leg went our way too at 19-18.

Usual full house in round 1. Hen A dropped one question in round which the B team picked up. full houses again in the first individuals. Hen A then dropped one question in each of rounds 4 and 5, both of which the B team picked up so half time score of 45-36 to the B team at which point the B team had not dropped a single question and had picked up whatever the A team had dropped.

The B team did drop one question in round 6 but unfortunately the A team dropped two, stretching the B teams lead to 11 points. Rounds 7 and 8 were both drawn before the A team finally struck back in round 9, winning that 9-4 to narrow the lead to 6 points. The B team then won the last round 6-4 to run out 79-71 winners.

B team also own the beer leg 20-18.

This match went trod the same predictable path as its predecessors - though it was closer than most of them have been of late.  It is thought that at some point in the past the A team beat the B team on one or maybe even two occasions.  The record of this momentous feat has been lost in the dusty archives but it probably dated back to the days when the B team manifested less quizzing ability and more charisma and that was a very long time ago indeed.  O tempora, o mores!

It's not easy to win quiz league games when the other side doesn't get any questions wrong. That's been said before, of course. Trouble for Red Lion B was that Bell A only missed two team questions all night. We missed a number of the individuals, to be fair, but given the subject matters that will not have come as a surprise. Bell A also picked up ten of the 14 bonus questions that came our way. I don't know if "Ivan meets GI Joe" by The Clash is because Russian soldiers are called Ivan, but it worked to get the two points. And good to see Gail "Corpus Christie" Trimble getting a mention, albeit not as part of the question. She was robbed. Bell A won the beer leg too, would have been a full house except we didn't remember Ridiculous Bowe.

Very close game with the lead changing hands regularly. The Sugar Loaf had the best of the first 5 rounds leading 37-35 at halfway. Red Lion A clawed back the lead to 61-59 after round 9. The final round proved a problem for both teams but RLA took it by 2-0 to take the match 63-59.

This was a reprise of last week's league match, with the same result in both the main quiz and the beer leg, and the same number of full-house rounds (4!)

Rounds 1 & 2 passed with little incident, yielding a 2 point advantage to the Squirrel going into the first individuals.  The home team picked up all their own questions and two bonuses to start round 4 8 points to the good.  That one was flat, but RLA dropped two more in round 5 to finish the half 13 points to the rear.

The second half started with two more full-houses, leaving RLA a figurative Olympus Mons to ascend.  They started this task promisingly in the individuals, clawing back 4 points to cut reduce the deficit from Greek proportions to something more reminiscent of Iceland.  Only temporarily, alas, as round 9 saw the Squirrel heave their reluctant carcasses another 3 points away, to leave RLA needing to take all 12 points in round 10 to get a draw.  In the event, both teams managed a stodgy 4 points apiece, to render a home win.

The beer leg went 17-16 to RLA

A closer match than the score line suggests. Four of the ten rounds were drawn. Of eleven bonus points, four came in the last round of the first half, three in the final round of the match. Bell A marches on to the semifinals, Hen A install themselves as favourites for the plate. To retain the plate, if memory serves. Neither side distinguished themselves in the beer leg, Bell took the cokes by being slightly less poor.

In a controversial selection decision Captain Keith extracted himself from his mum's garage to ask the questions allowing Richard to watch the Chelsea game and Barry Owen to come off the bench into the back four.
Round 1 - Guess what? 8 all.
Round 2 - we snuck a small lead through the power of whist.
Round 3 - Brakes and Sport give us a 5 point lead.
Round 4 - The Plough only pick up two points off Leighton Rees while we all dropped the motorways. A good round, 9 points clear.Going very well.
Round 5 - D'Oh!! Knitting and dyslexia both escaped us and we rushed the Hollywood sign while the Plough picked up two out of three bonuses and only dropped the trident. Half of our lead has gone and at half time it's 32-28.
Round 6 - 8 all again.
Round 7 - Was looking the same until the Plough let us pick up a bonus on LA Confidential
Round 8 - A good set of individuals all round but we picked a bonus up at Logan International Airport

22 enthusiasts from the Chiltern Quiz League warmed up for the new season by playing University Challenge. Held at The Bell in Chartridge, the event featured questions set by Keith Nickless from Farnham Common Sports Club. Players were divided into four teams. Unlike in the real game hosted by Jeremy Paxman on BBC2, teams were of five or six people but that didn't spoil the fun.
 
Because of the way the teams were set up, it's not possible to say that "The Bell won" or that "The Squirrel won". Suffice to say that the team featuring Colin from Sugar Loaf, Terri from Bell B, Jon from Hen B, and two others (whose names escape me but I'll give them a plug if they want to remind me...) won all three matches. Everyone else won one and lost two (work it out...) in six games that were all evenly and closely fought.
 
So everyone won or came second, how egalitarian is that? All must have prizes. Except there weren't any prizes, just a bit of fun for all, (and I suspect The Bell sold a few more pints than on the average Tuesday).
 
Thanks and eternal glory go to Peter Jones, for organising the whole thing.
